<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pianist <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> says he stopped playing in public in 1978 because he needed a short rest. <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> broke his long silence with a <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> performance during December's summit meeting between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. `` To be honest, I never thought the ` intermission' would go on for 10 years,'' <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> said in an interview published in Sunday's Dallas Morning News `` I guess it went on so long because I felt relaxed and was having such a good time simply living.'' Since the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> performance, he has had numerous offers but has so far accepted only one _ conductor <PERSON> Zubin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mehta </PERSON>'s invitation to accompany the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philharmonic </ORGANIZATION> on its first tour of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 15 years <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> will appear as soloist with the orchestra in concerts in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> during May and June, 30 years after he won the <ORGANIZATION> Tchaikovsky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Competition </ORGANIZATION>. He said he would perform in his home state of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> next season.
