<HEAD>Assemblies of God At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Swaggart, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Some facts and figures on the Assemblies of God church: _ Founded in 1914 during a convention in <LOCATION> Hot </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, the Assemblies of God moved its headquarters to <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, from <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> in 1918. It employs more than 1,300 people in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>: at the headquarters, its seminary, three colleges and a retirement center. _ The Assemblies of God is pentecostal, a branch of Christianity emphasizing personal experience of God, manifested in `` gifts of the spirit'' such as speaking in tongues and healing. _ It is the largest pentecostal demonination if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, claiming nearly 2.5 million adherents, plus 14 million overseas _ 9 million of them in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. _ There are nearly 11,000 Assemblies of God churches in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and more than 30,000 ministers _ about 3,700 of them women, according to a 1987 survey. _ The church is composed of 57 districts, primarily broken down by geographic boundaries. _ Ordained ministers and church delegates form the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a body which meets biennially to conduct church business, formulate procedures and policies, and elect top executive officers to the 13-member Executive Presbytery. The general superintendent, who is the top executive officer, is elected to a four-year term; all others are elected to two-year terms. _ Ministers can be disciplined not only for moral indescretion but also for straying from church doctrines, inefficency, being contentious or non-cooperative, or trying to assume dictatorial power over a congregation.
