<HEAD>Political Newcomer Is Fourth Cyprus President Since Independence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cyprus-Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON>, elected as <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>' fourth president since independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> 28 years ago, had never belonged to a political party or been involved in political activity until he decided to run for office The 56-year-old millionaire businessmen ran as an independent backed by the Moscow-oriented <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> AKEL </ORGANIZATION>, which controls about one-third of the votes among the 363,000 voters on the <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cypriot </ORGANIZATION> side of the divided <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island. On Sunday, he defeated a veteran conservative politician to become the nation's leader. Until his campaign, <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> concentrated on his research and marketing company, worth about $ 5 million. It is the largest in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. The campaign was a first for the communists as well. Until this poll, the party had always supported centrist candidates, never fielding its own man. But the millionaire's endorsement by the communists was not as contradictory as it sounds. His parents, <PERSON> Vassos </PERSON>, an eye doctor, and <PERSON> Phofo </PERSON>, a dentist, were founding members of the party in 1941. His father took the family to <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> in 1945 to fight on the communist side in the civil war. The pro-European <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> has stressed his political independence from the communists, particularly on foreign policy, and is expected to adhere to <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>' non-aligned status. The election of the urbane <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON>, an economist who speaks seven languages, breaks the Greek Cypriot nationalists' grip on power since independence. The island's first president, Archbishop <PERSON> Makarios </PERSON>, hero of the independence struggle in the 1950s, was elected for three five-year terms with huge majorities. His successor, <PERSON> Spyros </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyprianou </PERSON>, was considered his political heir and served for two terms _ but only with <ORGANIZATION> AKEL </ORGANIZATION> support, which was withdrawn in 1985. <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON>'s election breaks the mold. He has said his first priority is to break the deadlock between <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> and Turkish Cypriots and seek to reunite the island. It has been divided since the Turkish army invaded in 1974, after a short-lived coup by militant supporters of union with <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> that installed <PERSON> Nicos </PERSON> <PERSON> Sampson </PERSON> as president for eight days. All efforts to find a political settlement have foundered. But <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> has said he will form a national unity government and is willing to reopen negotiations without preconditions. <PERSON> Vassilou </PERSON>, who was born in <LOCATION> Famagusta </LOCATION>, now part of the breakaway Turkish Cypriot republic in the northern third of the island, was educated in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. He is married with three children.
