<HEAD>Workers Search Pond For Clues in Fatal Commuter Plane Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with comment from NTSB
official, saying debris shows that plane hit water first, and that
officials believe first officer, not the plane's captain, may have
been flying the plane. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `About 25...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MEG REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORRISVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investigators in motorboats raked the bottom of a shallow pond at <LOCATION> Raleigh-Durham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on Sunday, pulling up debris that may be a clue to a commuter plane crash that killed 12 people. No one survived Friday night's crash of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION> Flight 3378, which went down shortly after takeoff en route to <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. Because of debris found in the water, investigators believe the twin-engine turboprop hit the pond before plunging into a wooded area and exploding, officials said Sunday evening Earlier, they had said the plane had barely skimmed the pond, a flood reservoir, before crashing. Parts of the plane, including a portion of the hydraulic system, were found within 40 feet of the bank, said <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolstad </PERSON>. He also said that investigators believe the 28-year-old first officer, <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Digan </PERSON>, was flying the plane when it crashed Friday, because the captain, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, was talking to the control tower when the plane took off. `` The person that does the flying does n't usually do the radio,'' <PERSON> Kolstad </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Digan </PERSON>, who was hired by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION> last May, had 2,150 total flying hours and 450 in the Metro-III, the craft type involved in the crash. `` She was qualified,'' <PERSON> Kolstad </PERSON> said. `` There is no doubt about that.'' Weather at the time of the accident, although poor, was not so severe as to endanger the flight. Visibility on the runway was between 2,400 and 3,000 feet when the crash occurred. The flight could have taken off down to 1,600 feet, <PERSON> Kolstad </PERSON> said. Earlier, <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON>, said officials hoped that the search of the reservoir would show `` how -LRB- the plane -RRB- broke up. It helps determine the sequence of events.'' About 25 investigators, including some from the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>, sifted through the roped-off wreckage site on the pond's bank, peering at small bits of debris and examining larger plane parts for signs of malfunction. Beyond them, men in lifejackets piloted two motorboats around the surface of the pond, using poles and hooks to retrieve small pieces of crash debris. The pond measured about 4 feet deep and 75 yards wide, officials said. The debris will be used to determine the state and angle of the plane when it struck the bank, since the aircraft carried no flight data or cockpit voice recorders, <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> said. Neither is currently required by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> on commuter aircraft, although they will be as of March 1989, he said. `` If it was flying upside-down, that tells you something,'' he said. Some trees were broken and others were skinned as much as 200 yards beyond the water when the aircraft hit the wooded bank. The wreckage, including the entire silver tail, was strewn over an area measuring about 50 feet by 150 feet, <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> said. Rubble and bits of shiny metal still littered the tall grass. The largest plane piece, a red -, white - and blue-striped shard from the fuselage measuring about 15 feet, lay amid several broken pine tree Wheels from the landing gear had broken off their axle, while about 30 yards away, a piece of the aircraft's emergency door lay twisted in the mud The remains of the 10 passengers and two crew members were removed