<HEAD>Lights Of Western Maryland Community Form Outline Of United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEB RIECHMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LaVALE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For more than 20 years, the lights of this western <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> community have shimmered with national pride. As the lights of <PERSON> LaVale </PERSON> flicker at dusk, a near-perfect outline of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> begins to shine brightly from this residential community nestled in the foothills of the <ORGANIZATION> Alleghenies </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's an unusual happenstance. No one tried to make it,'' said <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> <PERSON> Dowell </PERSON>, who has lived for 25 years atop <LOCATION> Haystack </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> where the map is best viewed on a cold, clear winter night. `` I'm not sure who discovered it My wife mentioned it to me. She could n't believe it.'' A shopping center forms the U.S.-Canadian border. A well-lighted thoroughfare around <PERSON> LaVale </PERSON> is the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> is about a mile of motels, fast food restaurants and stores along <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 40. `` It's beginning to get a litle busy and distorted because of all the development in the LaVale area,'' said <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON>, who also lives in the 124-home Sunset View development on the mountain. `` As you come down the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> is starting to get a little out of proportion.'' `` Back five, 10 years ago, it was probably a little better,'' she said. `` We're not knocking the development, but we're losing our <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> is formed where <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 48 disappears behind a mountain ridge. The southern edge of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> is a bowling alley. A disfigured <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> appears where <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 40 vanishes around <LOCATION> Haystack </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION>. And the Gulf Coast is a grouping of homes and other establishments. `` It's the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Sunset </LOCATION> <LOCATION> View </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON>, a planner with the <ORGANIZATION> Allegany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. `` I guess just about everyone has heard of it. I do n't know if everyone believes it.'' The residential community of more than 7,200 has experienced a rush of commercial and residential development, especially since the 1960s, <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> said. `` We were worried about the mall when it opened up -LRB- in 1981 -RRB-, but it's actually a big <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruddell </PERSON>, a businessman who lives in the area. `` There's no <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. We have to do some more development.'' <PERSON> Ruddell </PERSON>, past chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Sunset </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> View </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the map is best seen in the winter when leaves have fallen from trees on Haystack Mountain. About nine months ago, members of the association thought about topping some trees to provide a better view, but scrapped the idea in favor of more pressing needs, he said. Some residents expressed concern that publicity would attract sightseers to Sunset View and create traffic, but others said most local residents either have already seen it, or have no interest in getting a glimpse of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in lights. `` Sometimes at night people stop out in front and you wonder what they're doing,'' <PERSON> Dowell </PERSON> said. `` But then you know what they're doing They're looking at the map.'' `` I remember one time _ it's been years ago _ one of my neighbors called and said, ` There's someone down in your garden with a tripod surveying,''' <PERSON> Dowell </PERSON> said. `` They were n't surveying. They were down there taking pictures of the map.''
