<HEAD>Half Of Crisis Hotline Staff Walks Out in Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After 30 years of handling people in crisis, the <ORGANIZATION> Suicide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prevention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> has a crisis of its own. Half the telephone hotline workers have walked out in a dispute over layoffs and control of the center. The workers went out on Jan. 1 and it has been a sometimes noisy dispute, with striking counselors picketing the center's offices and chanting `` down with the board'' during a recent closed-door meeting of directors. Despite the walkout, the crisis line handled more calls in January than it did the same month a year earlier, Executive Director <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Halfon </PERSON> said. In fact, the strike has prompted people to come forward to ask if the center needed their help. `` We were deluged with calls from people who read about it and -LRB- asked -RRB- how could they volunteer,'' <PERSON> Halfon </PERSON> said. In addition to the crisis line, the center operates a substance abuse clinic, a halfway house, an AIDS research project, an art therapy program and an annual curriculum for schools on substance abuse and suicide. Before the layoffs, the center _ excluding crisis line workers _ had about 90 full - and part-time employees The crisis line was staffed by about 80 volunteers and consultants. The latter are workers who started out as volunteers but have begun to receive part-time, $ 6-an-hour shifts. The crisis line workers walked out when 27 of the non-crisis line staffers were laid off and the hours of 15 others were cut back late last year. The layoff was strictly a `` budgetary concern,'' <PERSON> Halfon </PERSON> asserted, though she admitted, `` the timing was terrible, you know, December.'' The center's budget in 1985-86 was about $ 3 million, including revenue from contracts, grants, clinic fees and donations, she said. But in the last year, some grants have ended and contracts that provided government funding have not been renewed, she said, estimating the current budget at about $ 1.5 million. `` We are concerned with fulfilling that,'' she said. `` The cutbacks in just the layoffs will result in a savings of half a million dollars.'' The strikers, however, are particularly upset that among those laid off was the center's first employee, social worker <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Heilig </PERSON>, who served as a clinical consultant. `` We ca n't function without a clinical person in control,'' <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Meisler </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the strikers, said recently. `` The dismissal of one of the most well known and most experienced persons in the area of suicide prevention does n't make much sense,'' said <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Farberow </PERSON>, a psychologist who co-founded the center in 1958. <PERSON> Heilig </PERSON> did not return a telephone call for comment. In 1984, <PERSON> Farberow </PERSON> and the other founder, Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Litman </PERSON>, turned the center over to a board of directors composed of local business people so that they could focus on research. But the founders, who have remained as clinicians, want to regain control of the center. The board of directors met Feb. 7 to deal with the center's problems <PERSON> Halfon </PERSON> said the directors favored putting a member of the crisis line staff on the board, but she would not reveal what moves the board would take to resolve the overall problem of `` ultimate administrative control'' of the organization. `` That's the part that's in question. What's the best way to preserve the integrity and assets of the organization?''
