<HEAD>Fired FBI Agent Seeks Reinstatement; Changes Lifestyle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five months after the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> fired him, former agent <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> is grappling with a religious renewal that caused him to question his past, challenge his supervisors and lose his job. Wholesale changes are taking place in the life of a man who was 10 months away from settling into a quiet retirement when he was dismissed Sept. 11. After carrying a gun every day during 21 years of loyal <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> service, <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> now is a pacifist who denounces the `` immoral activities'' of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' involvement in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, 49, is selling his <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> home, where he and his wife, <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON>, raised four children. And he's pondering a total change in lifestyle while searching for a way to support his family the next 12 years until he can collect his federal pension. `` It would be inconsistent for me to continue being a heavy consumer knowing how many victims the American lifestyle demands,'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said recently. `` There's war in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> so we can continue to eat Big Macs, and I do n't want to contribute to that. We're scaling down our lifestyle to a more simplified life.'' His only income comes from speaking engagements and from teaching a sociology class at <ORGANIZATION> Bradley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Legal fees to fight his dismissal have eaten $ 13,000 out of the family savings _ perhaps part of the reason for the change in lifestyle. Clad in sneakers and jeans, <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> hardly resembled the man who spent two decades in foreign counterintelligence, investigating organized crime in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and hunting fugitives like anti-war activist <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Berrigan </PERSON>. His work twice won him commendations, but something was missing from his life. A devout Roman Catholic who once studied for the priesthood, <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> started taking religious study courses about 10 years ago. He earned his master's degree in 1985, and the transformation from a follower of <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> into a pacifist began to mature. It was then that <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> knew his beliefs would conflict with his role as chief counterintelligence operative in the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s five-man office here. But he never really thought it would lead to his dismissal. `` Refusing an order was something I'd never done before, and I knew an act of insubordination would cost me some sort of disciplinary action,'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said. `` I have religious beliefs they are bound to accommodate. There are office jobs, places I could work in the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. I would n't have to carry a gun. `` I think they overreacted in firing me. It was stupid. Look at all the notoriety it has caused.'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>'s life is in turmoil, but he seems content with his decision to refuse an order to investigate an anti-nuclear group suspected of vandalizing 11 Chicago-area military recruiting offices. `` I really feel I did the right thing,'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said. `` I do n't know if I could have lived with myself had I done anything differently. His firing occurred 10 months before his 50th birthday in June, when he would have been eligible for full retirement with 20 years service. `` I could have simply ignored the order, but I chose not to. I felt what we were doing was clearly investigating peace groups with the obvious intention of intimidating and harassing them. I thought the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> was ill-advised to do this and I told them.'' Despite his change of heart, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> negotiated with <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> and offered to reinstate him, with back pay, in December on the condition he never speak of the case again. He said he signed an agreement and mailed it to <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> headquarters but for some reason the deal collapsed. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> has refused to say why. This month, an administrative judge in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> ruled the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> was justified in firing <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>. At a hearing, <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said he could not take a human life, even if his or another person's life was endangered. He believes that was a key reason his dismissal was upheld. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> still hopes to reclaim his job and his pension, and an appeal is planned.
