<HEAD>Wildfire Jumps River, Burns Homes Near Whitehall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITEHALL, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A wildfire whipped by winds of up to 50 mph raced through a mountain valley south of here Sunday, destroying at least three homes and burning hundreds of acres of grassland, witnesses said. No injuries were reported. Firefighters from at least 10 volunteer fire departments in the rural area northwest of <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> battled the blaze, assisted by volunteers from the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lands </ORGANIZATION> and two mining companies. <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Giono </PERSON>, a dispatcher for the <ORGANIZATION> Jefferson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said the fire was first reported in early afternoon and had grown to 500 acres by early evening It remained uncontrolled, and those on the scene reported at least three homes destroyed, she said. The fire was centered about five miles south of this town of 1,000 and was headed eastward, not toward the town, officials said. The homes that burned were scattered rural residences. The wind `` is as bad as I've ever seen it,'' said <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, a trapper who lives on the south edge of town. `` The ... stuff was going faster than you could run.'' `` A lot of people lost their homes,'' <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> said, but noted he did not know exactly how many homes were destroyed. Authorities said it was believed that the fire was caused by a downed power line, but that had not been confirmed. Strong winds raked much of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> east of the Continental Divide on Sunday. There were widespread reports of damaged roofs, downed power line