<FIRST>r a PM-IcePatrol     02-22 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ice Patrol,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Meteorites From Moon Found in Antarctica</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 15-year search for meteorites in <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> has turned up thousands of meteorites, including six from the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION> and one possible rock from Mars, scientists say. Those seven meteorites _ solid bodies that travel through space and survive passage through the Earth's atmosphere _ have been the focus of years of scrutiny by scientists looking for insight on the composition of the two heavenly bodies. `` It has always been assumed that a lot of material should be falling off the moon from meteoritic impact,'' said <PERSON> Ursula </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON>, a geologist at the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>'s Center for Astrophysics here. `` We suspected that some of our meteorites came from the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION> before the Apollo missions.'' <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> was part of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> expedition that discovered the plum-sized rock weighing about four grams in January 1982. Japanese scientists have located five lunar meteorites in <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>. Scientists also are `` building a case'' for Martian origin of the meteorite found in 1979. Comparing the 1982 find with lunar samples collected by American astronauts, scientists found the meteorite closely matched highland materials returned by the Apollo 15, 16 and 17 crews. Analysis indicated that the fragment was blasted away from the moon by an asteroid impact about 100,000 years ago and hurled to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. The 66-year-old <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON>, who also teaches part-time at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said the lunar meteorite probably was traveling in space for between 1,900 and 2,500 years before crashing through the atmosphere and landing on the Antarctic ice. The Antarctic rock believed to be from Mars spent about 10 million years in space. Some of the 1,000 moon rocks retrieved in the Apollo missions have been dated at more than 4 billion years old _ a short time, by geologic standards. X-rays and gamma-rays of the moon's surface taken by Apollo orbiters have led scientists to believe the lunar meteorite may come from a crater on the far-eastern rim of the moon or on the unexplored dark side, <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> said. `` We went to six places on the moon and the Russians sent unmanned landers to three places,'' she said. `` We have no exact location for this composition anywhere.'' Annual <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> meteorite expeditions to <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> occur in the six weeks of the year when the continent is bathed in sunlight 24 hours a day. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Smithsonian </LOCATION> provide equipment and financing for research for the meteoritic expeditions, said <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON>, who has has made three trips to the 5-million-square-mile continent to search for meteorites. She said that since manned moon exploration stopped after the Apollo 17 mission in 1972, meteorite searches are crucial. `` It's one of the most vital and productive aspects of the space program,'' <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> said. `` As a matter of fact, in planetary exploration it's the only show in town. This all gives us more information _ without actually going up there _ about the evolution of the moon as a body.''
