<SECOND>PM-Train Derailment,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Train Derails, Spills Acid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAMINE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eleven cars of a 133-car <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> freight train derailed and spilled an acid solution into a creek, threatening the water supply for thousands of people, authorities said. No one was injured in Sunday's derailment in which one car spilled about 13,000 gallons of phosphatic fertilizer solution containing phosphoric acid into the creek leading to the <LOCATION> Lamine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Fussner </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. The <LOCATION> Lamine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, which feeds into the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, is the water source for nearby <LOCATION> Boonville </LOCATION>, a town of nearly 7,000 residents. Officials shut off the water intake valve to the community as a precaution, and residents were asked to conserve water, said Lt. <PERSON> Becky </PERSON> <PERSON> Loesing </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Cooper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> office. The <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> water department was monitoring its water supply from the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Phosphoric acid can irritate the skin and respiratory system, said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Alderson </PERSON>, environmental emergency specialist with the <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>. A 50-man cleanup crew worked into the night with backhoes and bulldozers to clean up and neutralize the acid. Trace elements of the acid were found in the <LOCATION> Lamine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, but no fish were killed, <PERSON> Fussner </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fussner </PERSON> said the cause of the accident, which occurred shortly before noon two miles from the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, was under investigation. Union Pacific officials called a cleanup contractor, who built a dam to try to prevent the fertilizer from further contaminating the <LOCATION> Lamine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Lime was hauled in to neutralize the acid, <PERSON> Alderson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fussner </PERSON> said the railroad encountered problems because the spill was in a remote area. No roads lead to the area, and all supplies were being brought in by train. The train was traveling from <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Platte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, when the accident occurred near this central Missouri town.
