<HEAD>Chirac Pulling Ahead In Crucial Race For Second Place</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REIMS, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, long mired in third place in opinion polls, has seen his presidential campaign take off, giving him an edge over rival conservative <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> with two months left before the vote. The first round of the election, April 24, has become in effect a primary election between <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>. Unless there is a stunning turnaround, one of the two will oppose a Socialist, probably incumbent President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, in the decisive May 8 runoff for a seven-year term. Policy differences between <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> are few and minor, so the campaign has focused on the contrasting personalities of the two men, and what their political advisers increasingly call `` le look.'' There is certainly no need for the voters to discover the candidates _ <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> has been a major national figure for 40 years, <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> for 15 years each. `` It's a question of sentiment, who looks better and talks better,'' said <PERSON> Bertrand </PERSON> <PERSON> Louapre </PERSON>, a Barre supporter interviewed on the edges of a cocktail reception during a <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> campaign swing Wednesday through <LOCATION> Reims </LOCATION>, capital of the Champagne country northeast of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. `` Personally, I've chosen <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Louapre </PERSON>, a construction engineer. `` Mr. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> has certainly taken off faster. He has much stronger support from his party.'' <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, a rangy, almost hyperactive figure, then displayed his formidable skills as a campaigner, moving swiftly through the crowd, but often stopping to grasp the hands of his supporters briefly in his own oversized hands. `` I think the premier is closer to people, and that's what will make him win,'' political science professor <PERSON> Alain </PERSON> <PERSON> Redslob </PERSON>, author of a book on <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, said in an interview. `` I think there's a strong movement beginning to lift off.'' `` The Barre style is that of a fairly cold man, who has wanted to give himself an image of rigor,'' <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s minister of overseas territories, recently said in a radio interview `` He is a man who is fairly secret and who ... frequently makes decisions alone.'' <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, a rotund economics professor who had never run for public office when he began his five-year term as premier in 1976, is widely respected but inspires little enthusiasm. He prides himself on telling people what they need to know, whether or not they want to hear it. `` They tell me to offer the French people a dream,'' <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> told a campaign rally in the southwestern city of <LOCATION> Poitiers </LOCATION> on Wednesday. `` But to dream, one must first go to sleep. I love my country too much, I respect my fellow citizens too much to lend myself to that.'' <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> says <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s government, which took over from the Socialists in March 1986, has made some good moves. He says he would take stronger action to boost French industry. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> has long had a solid lead in all published opinion surveys, while <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> trailed <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> thoughout last year. A poll published Jan. 16, the day <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> declared his candidacy, gave <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> 41 percent to 25 percent for <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> and 18.5 percent for <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>. But surveys published in the past two weeks have shown <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> pushing ahead. Friday's edition of the magazine <ORGANIZATION> Paris-Match </ORGANIZATION>, for exampale, reported 23 percent of those questioned planning to vote for <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, to 19 percent for <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, who says he will wait until mid-March to disclose his plans, remained far ahead with 36 percent. The questions were posed for Paris-Match and a radio network by the polling firm B.V.A., which between Feb. 1-4 interviewed 1,316 people who said they intended to vote. No margin of error was disclosed. <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, who insists on his independence from all political parties, is supported by the Union for <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, a loose grouping of five center-right parties that is part of <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s governing coalition The main event of <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s five-hour visit to <LOCATION> Reims </LOCATION> was a campaign rally that drew 7,000 supporters to a new exposition hall in the suburbs. Many arrived in buses chartered by <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s party, the Rally for the <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s most efficient political machine. Rather than give a speech, <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> answered questions from three men and two women chosen to raise issues of concern in the region. He defended <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s agricultural policies and promised to improve schools and universities so that students learn skills they need to find jobs. He also said he hoped to increase family allowances to mothers of three or more children to the minimum wage, about $ 825 a month, `` because they deserve it.'' The first question asked of <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, who is juggling duties as mayor of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, premier of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and member of a regional council in south-central <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, was how he can do all the work. `` I'm an optimist by nature,'' he replied, `` which probably gives me more energy to face problems.''
