 <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> of the federal mediation board. Negotiations began late Saturday at <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>'s request, and continued for six hours past the strike deadline. When talks broke off Sunday morning, <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> leaders promised that union members _ reservation clerks, customer service agents and other clerical staff _ would continue to work. The talks resumed in the afternoon at <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> headquarters here, but recessed after about a half-hour when the company rejected the mediator's call for arbitration, Genoese said. The dispute involves <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s attempts to cut costs by $ 35 million through concessions by the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>. The airline has said it needs about $ 540 million in concessions from its unionized employees during the next three years to ensure its survival. Asked about the major points of contention, <PERSON> Kriendler </PERSON> said, `` Let's say that the company long ago established a $ 35 million objective of achieving cost reductions. What is negotiable is how we reach the $ 35 million figure.'' The company does not view the amount as negotiable, <PERSON> Kriendler </PERSON> said, but the union maintains that it is. The company said it would maintain operations with replacement workers in the event of a strike. The <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> voted Friday not to support a <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>' strike, and pilots, flight attendants and flight engineers were not expected to honor picket lines. The Teamsters represent workers at airports in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATI