<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> says he is concerned about the Soviet role in setting up <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> peace talks even as the Soviets pledged to be more of a factor in negotiations. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, who favors an international conference to quell the violence in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, voiced doubts about Soviet involvement in arranging such a conference. The deaths of two Arabs Sunday brought the number of Palestinians killed by Israelis since the protests began Dec. 8 to 61, according to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> figures. `` What role the Russians will play depends on what role the international conference will play,'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> said Sunday in an interview from <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` This Week With <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinkley </PERSON>.'' `` I would never agree that any foreign country, <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> or other country, will make decisions instead of us or will try to force us to make a decision,'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> said. `` I do n't accept the Russian concept that an international conference should be an authoritative conference. I think it should be an authorizing conference, namely enabling the parties to negotiate among themselves freely.'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> said he understood that <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> share this view. The foreign minister said the conference `` should be like somebody that opens the door to a new era, but not somebody who replaces the residents in the house itself.'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> also acknowledged Sunday that he sent a handwritten note to Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mees