rity call of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> on the other,'' he said <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>, interviewed on <ORGANIZATION> CBS-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Face the Nation,'' welcomed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts to set up talks on resolving the <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> crisis and never was asked about a Soviet role `` I believe it's a very good idea to bring about a beginning of a talking,'' <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said. `` After all, the problem that we face can be solved only by political means. By military means, by force, we can bring about tranquility but not a solution. ... `` We have a very great respect and trust to Secretary <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. We believe that he is honest, decent human being and is trying his best to bring about a beginning of a talk.'' Former Secretary of State <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>, who appeared on the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> program, said negotiations should be conducted under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> auspices and not Soviet authority. `` I have the gravest doubts about an international conference,'' <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> said. `` I have grave doubts about a Soviet role, unless the Soviets are willing to ask of their Arab friends what we are going to propose to our <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> friends. So, I think that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> mediation is the best course.''
