<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> charged that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> lawmakers who are seeking to secure additional aid for the Contra rebels are egotistically toying with Nicaraguan lives. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said in a two-hour speech to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday that, despite a Feb. 4 vote in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> against a <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration request for more Contra aid, `` this chapter has not closed.'' President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, he said, will look for a way to get more money to the rebels by calling the assistance humanitarian aid. `` If the -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approves that type of financing, it would be erasing the word peace that it wrote when it voted against the funds, and would be putting -LRB- in -RRB- the word ` war,''' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said in the speech, broadcast over a government national radio network. `` That is the little game of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> where many interests, particularly egotistical, are involved and which is playing with life, hunger, security and the self-determination of the Nicaraguan people,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted against <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s plan to give the Contras a $ 36.2 million aid package that included about $ 3.6 million for weapons and ammunition to help them in their 6 -LCB- - year-old fight against the leftist Sandinista government Democrats prevailed in the vote, 219-211, after the party's leadership promised members there would be a later chance to vote on a package of Contra aid for food, clothing, medicine and shelter only A group of Democrats, together with one or two Republicans who voted against the president's plan, have been trying to draw up such an alternative. One proposal for the alternative aid request would give the Contras humanitarian aid at a rate of about $ 1.8 million a month. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said 26,500 people have been killed since the war began and 23,882 wounded. Other, unofficial sources, have put the death toll at more than 40,000. The war, he said, has cost the country $ 3.6 billion. Damage to the economy was estimated at $ 376 million last year, exceeding the $ 270 million in export earnings, he said. Even so, he said, the economy advanced at an inflation-adjusted rate of 1.7 percent in 1987. It contracted 0.4 percent in 1986. The inflation rate skyrocketed to 1,347 percent last year, well ahead of the 657 percent of the previous year. The government last week unveiled a new program to try to control runaway inflationm. It introduced a new cordoba currency, boosted prices of basic goods, increased salaries and cracked down on speculators.
