<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is likely to find out during a visit by Portuguese Prime Minister <PERSON> Anibal </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> this week if a proposed $ 46 million increase in military aid satisfies <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s request for more compensation for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> use of a major air base. <PERSON> Cavaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>'s first trip to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> since he took office last August is expected to be dominated by discussion of the base situation, which has injected a dose of sourness into an otherwise sweet relationship between the two <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> nations. <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> is getting $ 117 million in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance this fiscal year _ in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> only <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> got more _ but that was $ 30 million less than the fiscal 1987 payment. In the budget sent to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last week, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> would get $ 163 million. <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> wants $ 207 million a year, which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators pledged in 1983 they would make their `` best efforts'' to provide in return for a base-rights agreement that gives the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> access to <LOCATION> Lajes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Azores </LOCATION> islands. Besides being part of the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> chain of bases, <LOCATION> Lajes </LOCATION> is viewed by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> as an indispensable refueling point for mammoth transports heading for the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The grumbling in <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION> is similar to 