agreeing to congressional request to keep Midgetman program alive.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The new Pentagon budget has reopened the bitter fight between <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration over the MX nuclear missile and how to build <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future arsenal of land-based atomic weapons. And in the latest round _ on a possible successor to the MX missile _ past administration critics have gained grudging support from an unusual quarter _ <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>. Although he personally does n't think much of the Midgetman missile, the congressionally designated heir apparent to the MX, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> has agreed to request enough funding to keep the project alive until a new administration can make the final decision. The budget sent to the Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last week proposed $ 807 million to buy a dozen more of the 10-warhead MX weapons, along with $ 793 million for a new method of basing the giant missiles aboard trains. The current plan is to put 50 of the weapons into silos on <ORGANIZATION> Warren </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in southeastern <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> also wants to build 50 more and deploy two each aboard 25 specially-built trains. But <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> last week that if it were up to him, he would put all 100 MX weapons on the trains. `` We badly need a survivable missile system,'' he explained. That statement echoed criticisms by MX opponents, who claimed during a series of long fights in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s first term that putting the MX into land-based silos would make the missiles vulnerable to a first strike by accurate Soviet missiles. Former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> strongly disagreed and pushed hard for approval for 100 of the weapons. They were to replace some of the aging Minuteman missiles which now make up the heart of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s land-based nuclear missile force. After a series of long fights, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> finally agreed to put 50 of the weapons in land-based silos and then approved the single-warhead Midgetman weapon as a successor to the MX. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> agreed with that plan, but later <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> decided to try to win approval for the second 50 MX weapons. Even as the budget was unveiled Thursday, MX critics were lining up to oppose the railroad-basing plan. `` The debate concerning survivability has been raging for years and apparently will continue,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Mavroules </PERSON>, D-Mass., one of the chief opponents of the weapon in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s first term `` Based on the available data, serious questions remain regarding the safety and survivability of that type of deployment system,'' said <PERSON> Mavroules </PERSON>. `` Because of these lingering questions, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must be concerned about the rashness of this proposal.'' Another critic, Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> AuCoin </PERSON>, D-Ore., said `` rail garrison would be vulnerable to more than Soviet missiles Because commercial rail lines would be used, the threat of terrorism and sabotage must be considered serious.'' `` Additionally, in light of the recent problems surrounding the safety of our nation's rail system, it is not pleasant to contemplate the thought of nuclear warheads being trundled around through populated areas.'' Both <PERSON> Mavroules </PERSON> and <PERSON> AuCoin </PERSON> promised to try to eliminate all money for the rail-basing plan. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> also said he wanted to kill the Midgetman program because budgetary restraints made it necessary to choose between Midgetman and the MX. But to meet a congressional request, he included $ 200 million to keep the program alive until a new president takes office next year. That met with the approval of Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and a Midgetman supporter `` I felt it would be a mistake to zero the program and I wanted it kept alive for the next administration. This money seems to me to meet that request,'' said <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, who helped defeat an attempt to kill the Midgetman program two months ago. Of the 50 MX weapons to be deployed, 33 are now in their silos, but only 20 of those are operational because of problems in delivering the guidance systems. But <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said that all 50 will be in the silos by the end of 1988.
