<FIRST>r w PM-FlexibleFuel     02-22 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flexible Fuel,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dual-Fuel Cars Seen as Protection Against Price Hikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cars and trucks capable of switching from one fuel to another could discourage future oil price increases by foreign producers, the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says. The department says dual-fuel motor vehicles, in sufficient numbers on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> highways, would offer that benefit even if the foreign oil producers also supplied the second, non-petroleum fuel. In the first of a series of reports planned for this year on alternate fuels, the department says enough twin-fuel vehicles would have to be in use to switch away from about 1 million barrels of oil a day. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> uses almost 17 million barrels of oil per day, a bit more than a third of it imported, and five-eighths of it devoted to transportation. It would take a decade of spending several billion dollars a year to build the plants and distribution system necessary for significant switching ability to methanol or natural gas, the report said. The department and many in the oil industry are worried that imports will account for 60 percent of supplies by the middle of the next decade. That would give the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> leverage it has been unable to exercise in the surplus-sloshed soft markets of recent years, because <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> will then have the only spare production capacity available in the world. The department promised more detailed reports on the experience of other countries, supply prospects, environmental effects and a cost-benefit analysis later this year. The most recent report was described as `` context and analytical framework.'' `` Whatever strategy the country goes with has got to withstand cyclical swings in oil prices,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, director of the office of policy, planning and analysis, whose staff did the work. Though other approaches should be pursued, only methanol `` appears at this stage of the assessment to be a fuel with clear potential for meeting a significant percentage of this country's transportation fuel demand in the short run,'' the study said The study director, <PERSON> Vito </PERSON> <PERSON> Stagliano </PERSON>, estimated that a dual-fuel car would cost $ 50 to $ 350 more in volume production. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> already has produced several hundred. To cut oil demand by 1 million barrels a day, the report estimated these needs: _ Ten new methanol plants each year for a decade, costing a total of $ 20 billion to $ 25 billion _ Development of 10,000 to 30,000 alternative-capable retail outlets a year, with an eventual total of 150,000 stations costing more than $ 5 billion in all No cost estimate was given for changing pipelines, barges and other distribution facilities to methanol. _ Methanol-compatible vehicles entering the motor vehicle fleet at a rate of 1.5 million to 8 million a year There are more than 170 million cars, trucks and buses on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> highways now. Except in emergencies, motorists would not use methanol unless it were `` perceptibly less expensive'' _ more than two gallons of methanol are needed to provide the mileage obtainable with a gallon of gasoline. `` Nevertheless, it is conceivable that the very prospect of seeing large volumes of the demand for oil translate into demand for alternative fuels will in itself discourage future increases in oil prices,'' the report said. Methanol is made most cheaply from natural gas. The report observed that although the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the world's biggest methanol producer, it has been a net importer since 1982, and <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> countries can produce at half the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cost. A future methanol market `` could be dominated by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> oil suppliers, or it might be one in which those countries play a less significant role,'' the report said. Middle Eastern countries could supply <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> methanol needs economically, but `` any increase in the total potential supply of liquid fuels in the world should tend to enhance <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> energy security, because it would cause the world energy market to loosen up,'' the report said. A methanol cartel that raised prices would call forth increased supplies from elsewhere, just as oil output expanded elsewhere in the 1970s after <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> began steep price hikes, the report said. `` Because feedstocks of natural gas are more widely distributed, even greater price competition would result in this case,'' it said.
</TEXT>
