<HEAD>California Makes Most from Military Contracts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> continued to pace the nation last year in the receipt of <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> contracts despite suffering a significant drop in awards compared to the previous year, new reports show. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> also maintained its position as the state with the largest <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> payroll, as well as the No. 1 destination for military retirees. Payroll and pension checks combined pumped $ 12.7 billion into the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> economy in fiscal 1987, the reports show. Nationally, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> awarded $ 147.12 billion in contracts for work performed inside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> during fiscal 1987 _ a drop of $ 2.1 billion compared to fiscal 1986. It also paid out $ 84.5 billion in payroll and pensions during the year to individuals retired or working inside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, up $ 2.7 billion compared to the previous year. Of that $ 84.5 billion grand total, $ 26.3 billion went to pay civilian employees in the 50 states; $ 34 billion went to pay active-duty personnel in the 50 states; $ 5.5 billion went to pay reservists and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> members, and $ 18.7 billion went to retirees. The new figures are contained in two annual statistical reports _ one known as the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> `` Atlas'' and the other entitled `` Prime Contract Awards by State'' _ that attempt to show how <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spending is affecting the 50 states. Those figures will be augmented in the coming months with additional reports on such things as the nation's top defense contractors; total contract actions, including work outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and civilian and military employee comparisons. The state statistics for fiscal 1987 show that the 12 months ending last Sept. 30 produced some unusually wide swings in Pentagon spending patterns. For example, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> easily paced the nation with military contractors in that state winning $ 24.5 billion in awards. But that total represented an 11.6 percent drop, or $ 3.2 billion less than the $ 27.7 billion in contracts awarded in fiscal 1986. Similarly, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> tumbled from second place to fourth in the contract rankings because of 20.9 percent decline in awards, while <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> climbed from eighth to fifth thanks to a whopping 44.5 percent increase in awards. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> finished the fiscal year with awards totaling $ 8.65 billion, while <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> finished with $ 7.8 billion. Second place went to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with $ 9.6 billion, while third place went to <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> with $ 8.69 billion. The remainder of the top 10 included <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> at sixth place with $ 6 billion; <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> with $ 5.8 billion; <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> with $ 5 billion; <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> with $ 4.75 billion, and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> with $ 4.5 billion. Even setting aside contracting, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> benefited the most from the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s presence, with $ 12.7 billion flowing into the state in pension checks and salaries for civilian, active-duty and reserve employees. <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> rounded out the top five, retaining the same positions in fiscal 1987 they had the year before. <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> saw $ 8.8 billion flow into its borders in total compensation, compared to $ 6.6 billion for <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, $ 5.6 billion in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and $ 3.2 billion in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. The remainder of the top 10 included <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> with $ 3 billion in total compensation; <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> with $ 2.74 billion; <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> with $ 2.66 billion; <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> with $ 2.4 billion, and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> with $ 2.3 billion. Breaking down those figures to focus on retiree compensation, the most money again flowed into <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ totaling $ 2.7 billion. Next was <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> with $ 1.9 billion, followed by <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> with $ 1.88 billion; <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> with $ 1.4 billion and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> with $ 682.5 million.
