<HEAD>Effectiveness Of Anti-Drug Programs Needs Evaluating,
Investigators Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal watchdog says it is time to use a few of the millions of dollars spent annually on anti-drug education to answer a simple question: What works and what does n't? That was the conclusion reached by Inspector General <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON> after he was asked by the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to evaluate a variety of programs. In weeks of studying <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s `` Just Say No'' campaign and two other antidrug efforts targeted at the very young, investigators found more questions than answers. The main recommendation in a preliminary version of <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON>'s report is that federal agencies `` should develop an evaluation strategy to include long - and short-term evaluations of the implementation and effectiveness of youth drug education programs Specifically, he said those strategies should be devised by the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the Alcohol, <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON>, charged with monitoring programs of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, agreed to discuss the study after The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> obtained a draft copy. He acknowledged that the document lacks the precision typically associated with IG reports, but said that should not be read as an indictment of any of the programs surveyed. In fact, he said, `` It looks like they're on the right track.'' But the former <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent said his investigators' attempts to determine whether the programs are `` just fluff and puffery or real'' were hampered by lack of measurable data. `` There is no evidence that seems to be available to tell us how successful these programs are,'' he said. `` I think we've put the first layer in, but if you want to have an ongoing, effective program we're going to get more sophisticated. You can not get sophisticated until you start developing some objective criteria and some instruments to measure progress. `` Our concern is that if these programs satisfy themselves that they can relax on their laurels and sort of coast on to ever increasing success, I think they're deluding themselves. If we want to increase the effectiveness of the programs we are going to have some sort of measurement that would allow them to know what are successful techniques versus the less successful techniques.'' <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON> added: `` You're not talking about hoards of money to do that. You're just saying that somewhere along the line they're going to have to set aside some resource to look at how they can go about developing a model they can measure. And developing such measurements, he said, are beyond the scope of the IG's office. In addition to `` Just Say No,'' a loosely knit association of local efforts operating under a private foundation, the IG study looked at the <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clubs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Smart Moves'' and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parents </ORGANIZATION>' `` Drug Free Youth.'' `` These programs sort of spontaneously came into being,'' <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON> said, noting that each is financed almost totally at the community level. He said each of the three should consider developing its own criteria for measuring success and that someone _ perhaps the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alcohol </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> _ `` might want to ask which one is best.''
