<TEXT>
 A moderate earthquake shook central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, jarring residents awake as it sent dishes rattling and house beams creaking but caused no injuries or major damage, officials said. The quake, measuring 3.9 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, hit at 11:43 p.m. Sunday, and was centered about 40 miles west-northwest of <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Finn </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>'s seismology laboratory in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>. Shaking was felt over a broad area in <LOCATION> Kern </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Obispo </LOCATION> counties, and as far north as <PERSON> Paso </PERSON> <PERSON> Robles </PERSON>, about 75 miles away. `` It rattled some dishes and caused some attic beams to creak, but after the initial fright, most of our callers settled right down,'' said <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Obispo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's Sgt. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON>. `` We've had about a dozen calls, spread out over about 40 miles,'' <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> said. `` It woke people up, but there were n't any reports of injury or damage.'' Residents in <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION> and nearby <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> felt the ground shake, but <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> police officers said they barely noticed the temblor. The <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. An earthquake of 3.5 on the open-ended scale can cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage.
