<HEAD>Crew And Passengers Foil Attempted Hijacking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Passengers and crew members on a <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> flight today prevented a Taiwanese man from hijacking the plane to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> by hitting him over the head and wrestling him to the floor, the airline said. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 jetliner was carrying 114 people, including one American, on a flight from <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> to the southern port city of <LOCATION> Kaohsiung </LOCATION>, 240 miles away, when the hijack attempt by the 29-year-old man occurred. The man, an employee at a knife grinding shop, was carrying two fake grenades made of wood and a slip of paper from a fortuneteller predicting a year of bad luck, the airline said at a news conference. According to the airline, the would-be hijacker was subdued after a crew member hit him on the head with a `` hard object.'' No injuries were reported among the other 106 passengers and seven crew members aboard the jetliner. The plane landed at <LOCATION> Kaohsiung </LOCATION> and later returned to <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> where members of the cabin crew appeared at a press conference. <PERSON> Stewardess </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lin </PERSON> said she was passing out drinks to the passengers about 20 minutes after takeoff when the would-be hijacker, <PERSON> Chien </PERSON> <PERSON> Chu-yuan </PERSON>, handed her a slip of paper demanding the plane be diverted to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. `` He threatened on the slip of paper that he would kill all of us with his two grenades if we did n't fly to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>,'' she said. The man later said he wanted to go to <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION>, but crew members said he was nervous and probably meant <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. The would-be hijacker claimed to have two partners, but the airline has ruled out that possibility. The stewardess asked four stewards for help as most passengers remained unaware of the unfolding drama. The stewards and a few passengers then pounced on the hijacker when he tried to show the phony grenades to the passengers and subdued him after a 10-minute scuffle. `` We asked the captain to fly in circles and told the hijacker we would divert to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>,'' said steward <PERSON> Chi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hsi-an </PERSON>. Police said the would-be hijacker, a native Taiwanese who worked in his brother's knife grinding shop, was in custody in <LOCATION> Kaohsuing </LOCATION>. Attempted hijacking can carry the death sentence in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. Officials were unsure how many foreigners were aboard the plane besides the one American. Among the passengers was <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Yueh-ying </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Kaohsiung </LOCATION> county magistrate who is an opposition member. In 1985, an attempted hijacking occurred aboard a <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 flying the same route with 107 passengers. In that incident, a homesick army sergeant who wanted to see his parents was overpowered by crew members after he seized a stewardess.
