<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Every year the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> manages to find volunteers to taste more than 100 bottles of homemade wine for the <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wine </ORGANIZATION> and Seafood Festival. It's hard work, some of the 27 volunteer judges tapped this year said over the weekend. `` We taste a lot of different wines and try to decide, try to be objective,'' <PERSON> Opal </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. `` We do n't want to say anything bad about them, but some of them ...'' She trailed off, perhaps not wishing to leave a bitter aftertaste. Since wine can be made from nearly anything organic, some of the entries are, well, unusual. Garlic, dried kiwi fruit, rose petals, zucchini and even sauerkraut have found their way into bottles during past competitions. `` A little sauerkraut wine is good on a cold night,'' judge <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Swafford </PERSON> said dryly. Stomach aches are unlikely, since the rules say the judges are supposed to sniff, swirl, taste and spit. Still, the volunteer judges must sign a waiver releasing the chamber from any blame should they be struck with a sudden illness, and nobody else is allowed the taste the amateur wines that are displayed at the festival. The festival, which opened Friday and runs through Feb. 28, allows the public to taste commercial wines, and compare their choices with results from a panel of professional judges.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Whales are coming to <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. The Shedd Aquarium says its Oceanarium, a $ 43 million expansion project that should be completed by 1990, will exhibit six whales, four dolphins, several sea otters and a rookery of penguins. The Oceanarium design calls for huge rocks, cliffs and 35-foot trees on 1.8 acres of what was <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> before 30 million gallons of water was siphoned so construction could begin below lake level in August. To give the illusion the whales are in the ocean, a 600-foot-long 35-foot-high picture window will overlook the lake from behind their tanks. `` I've got a gut feeling that we might even have to turn people away,'' aquarium director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Braker </PERSON> said recently as cranes pounded 75-foot-long steel pilings for the foundation. `` We had 1.1 million visitors in 1987, and with the Oceanarium, I think we may hit 2 million.'' Three milk-white, 15-foot beluga whales will be airlifted from <LOCATION> Churchill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, aquarium officials said. As whales go, Manitobas are small, but the largest animal now at <LOCATION> Shedd </LOCATION> is a 7-foot nurse shark. Three more <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> black whales, about the size of <LOCATION> Manitobas </LOCATION>, will be brought from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the aquarium staff said. <PERSON> Braker </PERSON> said <PERSON> Shedd </PERSON>, which opened in 1929 and is the world's largest indoor aquarium at 230,000 square feet, `` needed a good shot in the arm to bring it out of many years of being static. Money for the Oceanarium includes $ 5 million each from the state and the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>. The aquarium has spent $ 8 million and hopes to raise the remainder of the $ 25 million price tag through donations.
