<HEAD>Demonstrators Injure Police, Take Hostages In New Caledonia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police clashed with about 100 separatist demonstrators today at a hospital construction site, and authorities said 10 officers were injured and a dozen were taken hostage in the melee. <PERSON> Philippe </PERSON> <PERSON> Berges </PERSON>, chief of staff at the High Commission, said the protesters at <LOCATION> Poindimie </LOCATION> on the east side of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> island were demanding a halt to work on the site. The work began Friday. `` There will be no negotiations until the gendarmes have been freed,'' <PERSON> Berges </PERSON> said. He said the team of gendarmes, a police force under military direction, showed great restraint by not firing their weapons when they were attacked with stones and sticks. The gendarmes fired tear gas grenades to get free of the demonstrators, but some of the officers were captured and disarmed. <PERSON> Berges </PERSON> said reinforcements were being sent to the scene, where <PERSON> Melanesian </PERSON> supporters of the <ORGANIZATION> Kanak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, known by its French initials <ORGANIZATION> FLNKS </ORGANIZATION>, are opposed to building of the hospital on what they say is land belonging to the <LOCATION> Tieti </LOCATION> tribe. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>, a French overseas territory of 145,000 people about 1,100 miles east of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, voted against independence in a referendum last September. The indigenous Melanesians make up 42.6 percent of the population, Europeans 37.1 percent and other nationalites the rest.
