<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Now that the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> has been saved, readers and employees wonder what the nation's oldest continuously published newspaper will look like under the new owner, and whether he'll stop its money-losing ways. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON>, who is buying the tabloid from <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> for $ 37.6 million, spent Sunday talking with advisers about what direction to take the Post. The paper's 10 unions agreed Saturday to $ 22 million in concessions that <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON> said were necessary to keep the paper alive. That includes eliminating 130 of the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>'s 1,200 jobs. <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON> is widely thought to want to back away from the paper's emphasis on stories of sex, crime and scandal It will remain a tabloid, but `` there will be a change in format,'' said his spokesman, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubenstein </PERSON>. `` There'll be changes in headlines, in the front page, in the emphasis of the paper.'' But, <PERSON> Rubenstein </PERSON> added, <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON> `` still wants it to be feisty and provocative.'' <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> bought the paper in 1976 and fashioned it after the British tabloids. Soon readers were seeing such headlines as `` HEADLESS BODY IN TOPLESS BAR,'' which ran above a story about a homicide in a tavern. They saw a photo of Prince <PERSON> Rainier </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Monaco </LOCATION> looking into, and making an obscene hand gesture at, a Post photographer's lens. The caption read: `` THE PRINCE GIVES US THE FINGER.'' And then there was the story about <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s reported psychological problems, featuring a photograph doctored to show readers what he would look like dressed as a woman, complete with lipstick and earrings. <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON>, a real estate developer and businessman worth an estimated $ 500 million, has approved a $ 2 million promotional campaign for the newspaper, said <PERSON> Rubenstein </PERSON>. According to his agreement with <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON> promised to keep the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> in operation for at least one year after he takes over March 7. The <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> lost about $ 17 million before taxes last year, and about a quarter of its advertising in the last few months. Its circulation has dropped from 700,000 to 500,000, partly because of a retrenchment in areas outside metropolitan <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. A $ 1 million marketing study commissioned by <PERSON> Kalikow </PERSON> `` shows the paper already appeals to a fairly well-to-do audience,'' <PERSON> Rubenstein </PERSON> said.
