<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Set-Aside,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court To Decide Affirmative Action Issue From Virginia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to study a key affirmative action issue _ the power of local governments to require minority participation in public works projects. The justices said they will hear an appeal by <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, officials seeking to revive a so-called set-aside program for construction industry businesses owned by minorities. The court previously expressed interest in examining the issue when on Jan. 19 it asked the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to comment on a construction company's challenge to a set-aside program in the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> area. But the justices stopped short of announcing whether they will hear arguments in the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> dispute. In the <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> case, the 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled last September that the city's preferential treatment for minority businesses approved in 1983 is an unconstitutional form of reverse discrimination. The <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> plan would require the prime contractor on any city building contract to subcontract at least 30 percent of the value of the project to firms that are at least one-half minority owned. The minorities covered by the plan were blacks, Hispanics, Orientals, Indians, Eskimos and Aleuts. The appeals court, in its 2-1 decision, relied heavily on a 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that struck down an affirmative action plan in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> designed to protect from lay-offs minority teachers with less seniority than whites. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in that case said preferential treatment of minorities must be narrowly tailored to avoid hurting whites. The court restricted the power of employers to adopt affirmative action programs when there has not been proof those employers practiced past discrimination. Supporters of local set-aside programs, on the other hand, point to a 1980 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may require 10 percent of federal public works contracts be earmarked for minority-controlled businesses. An eventual <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling on local set-aside programs would have far-reaching impact. Most states and some 160 local governments have such programs, according to a study by the <ORGANIZATION> Minority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Education Fund. The 4th Circuit court, in striking down the <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> plan, said the city's program was adopted on scant evidence of past discrimination. The appeals court noted that minorities comprise about half of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>'s population and that minority-owned businesses had received less than 1 percent of the value of the city's public building contracts. But the appeals court said there are few minority-owned businesses in the city area, and there was no evidence they had been victims of past discrimination. `` General population statistics suggest, if anything, more of a political than a remedial basis for the racial preference'' quota in the set-aside program, the 4th Circuit court said. `` There has been no showing that qualified minority contractors who submitted low bids were passed over.'' The appeals court also said the 30 percent quota `` was chosen arbitrarily. The figure simply emerged from the mists.'' `` The <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> ordinance reflects the most casual deployment of race in the dispensation of public benefits. It prefers some, and in so doing diminishes the rights of all,'' the appeals court said. A coalition of groups representing local and state governments urged the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to reinstate the <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> plan. The coalition said it would reopen old wounds and discourage affirmative action if governments must first show past discrimination before adopting remedial programs. The coalition groups are the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Counties </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>'s plan was challenged by the J.A. <ORGANIZATION> Croson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> after its bid _ the only one submitted _ to install stainless steel urinals and water closets at the city jail was rejected. City officials refused to award the contract after <PERSON> Croson </PERSON> said there was only one unqualified minority contractor that could help on the project. The company said the cost of the project would rise by $ 7,663 if the minority contractor were used. The city then called for new bids. The case is <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Croson </PERSON>, 87-998.
