<HEAD>Court to Decide Search Warrant Issue in Florida Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to decide when police need court warrants before searching from helicopters for marijuana growing in fenced-in yards. The justices said they will study a <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that a helicopter search by sheriff's deputies in <LOCATION> Pasco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> four years ago violated the right of privacy. The nation's highest court in 1986 ruled that a warrantless search by <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, police in an airplane had not violated privacy rights. In that case, police spotted marijana plants growing in a fenced-in yard while flying at a lawful altitude of 1,000 feet. Voting 5-4 then, the justices said the Constitution's Fourth Amendment, which bans unreasonable government searches, `` simply does not require the police traveling in public airways at this altitude -LRB- 1,000 feet -RRB- to obtain a warrant in order to observe what is visible to the naked eye.'' In the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> case, <LOCATION> Pasco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> deputies received an anonymous tip that <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> was growing marijuana in his yard. Unable to tell what plants were growing in a greenhouse in the yard, the deputies flew over the yard in a helicopter, at an altitude of about 400 feet. From there, they could look into missing panels in the greenhouse roof. Based on what they saw, the deputies obtained a search warrant and entered <PERSON> Riley </PERSON>'s yard, seizing 44 marijuana plants. <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> challenged the helicopter search, seeking to block prosecutors from using the marijuana plants as evidence against him. The <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last July 9 ruled for <PERSON> Riley </PERSON>, stating that the helicopter search violated <PERSON> Riley </PERSON>'s reasonable expectation of privacy under the Fourth Amendment. The state court said the 1986 decision did not authorize `` an unlimited right to any type of examination of residential property from the air.'' The state court added, `` Surveillance by helicopter is particularly likely to unreasonably intrude upon private activities ... because of a helicopter's virtually unlimited maneuverability and observational capabilities.'' It noted that fixed-wing airplanes are not authorized to fly lower than 500 feet in the area where the search occurred. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> prosecutors filed the appeal acted on today. The case is <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Riley </PERSON>, 87-764.
