<HEAD>Court Will Decide Iowa Case on Taxing Oil and Natural Gas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to decide whether states may tax any income from oil and natural gas extracted from the Outer Continental Shelf. The court said it will hear an appeal by <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> challenging an <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> tax. The state tax is designed to be imposed on that portion of a company's income derived from doing business in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> said it was improper for state officials to include any revenue from offshore gas and oil in determining the company's taxable income <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> said the state tax violates a 1953 federal law authorizing exploration and production of Outer Continental Shelf oil and gas. The shelf is underwater land more than three miles off the shore of any state. The land is owned by the federal government and leased to private companies. The <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld the state tax last October. It said the levy `` is in no way dependent upon the exercise of legislative jursidiction on Outer Continental Shelf lands'' that the 1953 federal law was intended to prohibit. Including revenue from <ORGANIZATION> OCS </ORGANIZATION> oil and gas `` apparently aids in obtaining an accurate measure of the tax to be imposed as a result of <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> activities,'' the state court said. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration agreed with the ruling of the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> court but urged the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to use <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION>'s appeal to settle the dispute. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANI