<HEAD>Court Will Study Illinois Tax on In-State Calls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to judge the validity of a 5 percent tax <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> imposes on all telephone calls charged to in-state numbers. The court said it will study arguments that the tax interferes impermissibly with interstate commerce. The tax is assessed at a flat rate on all calls, intrastate and interstate, charged to <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> service addresses. Two state residents, <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McTigue </PERSON>, challenged the law in a class-action lawsuit three years ago in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> joined the case later, seeking to recover taxes already paid. From Sept. 15, 1985, to July 1986, <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> paid $ 2.6 million in taxes under the challenged <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Excise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld the tax last June 24, reversing a state appeals court ruling that had invalidated it. The appeals court had said <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> `` is attempting to tax the entire cost of an interstate act which takes place only partially in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>.'' The appeals court had added, `` This tax ... discriminates against interstate commerce and it is not related to services provided in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>.'' The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> acknowledged that <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> is taxing the `` gross charge'' of an entire interstate call `` even though the benefits it affords are limited to that portion of the communication occurring within the state.'' But it said the tax does not unduly burden interstate commerce. The two state residents and <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> filed separate <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeals, and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taxpayers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> urged the justices as a `` friend of the court'' to strike down the tax. Its brief argued: `` If <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> attempted to tax <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parcel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> on the entire value of its service for all packages picked up in the state, regardless of where they were delivered, that tax would fall before the -LRB- Constitution's -RRB- commerce clause ... Telecommunications companies, whether they are in the telephone, telegraph or electronic data transmission business, provide a service which, for many purposes, is functionally identical.'' The cases are <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> vs. Sweet, 87-826, and <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> vs. Sweet, 87-1101.
