<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand a ruling that forces <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, city officials to justify in federal court a zoning ordinance limiting where adult bookstores may be opened for business. The court, without comment, refused to hear arguments aimed at squelching a lawsuit challenging the ordinance. The ordinance limits the area where adult bookstores may locate to a portion of downtown <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON> representing less than 1 percent of the land within the city's 25.3 square miles. Adult bookstores are defined by the ordinance as those where sexually explicit materials comprise more than 20 percent of the stock in trade. So any business establishment, anywhere in the city, may have up to 20 percent of its trade in adult materials. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Christy </PERSON>, who sought to operate an adult bookstore in an area not zoned for adult entertainment, sued the city. She sought to block enforcement of the zoning ordinance. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> refused to block enforcement, ruling that the ordinance is not impermissibly restrictive. `` The 20 percent requirement provides a beneficial way for decentralization of the adult book business,'' he said. `` By sanctioning the selling of adult books and other books together, the city has eliminated most of the well-known problems of urban blight that result from concentrations of these bookstores without sacrificing its citizens' First Amendment freedoms,'' <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> said. But the 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled last July 23 that <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> was wrong. `` A city can not arbitrarily limit the exercise of First Amendment rights,'' the appeals court said. `` A limitation of adult materials to 20 percent of a bookseller's wares conditions the constitutional right to speak in one way on the bookseller's willingness to speak in a different way 80 percent of the time. The appeals court sent the case back to <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> for further study after saying it found no evidence `` of a legitimate government objective for the passage of this zoning ordinance.'' In the appeal acted on today, city officials argued, among other things, that the Constitution's First Amendment does not guarantee the existence of adult bookstores if `` the right of access to such materials may be accommodated in other ways.'' The case is <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Christy </PERSON>, 87-649.
