<HEAD>Court Will Hear Appeals in Black Lung Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to hear appeals by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and coal mining companies seeking to block the possible award of billions of dollars in black lung disease benefits to thousands of miners. The court said it will review a ruling that the government must reopen some previously rejected claims for benefits. The administration said the ruling by a federal appeals court, if extended nationwide, could force officials to re-examine 94,000 claims at potentially tremendous cost to the overburdened fund that pays benefits to miners afflicted with the disease. The 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last March ruled that thousands of miners seeking the benefits had been unfairly denied a hearing. The ruling applied to miners with less than 10 years of work in the mines whose claims were denied in the late 1970s and early 1980s. The appeals court said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> must take a fresh look at the claims under liberalized standards adopted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1977. The appeals court applied the ruling to miners who failed to exhaust their administrative remedies or who missed deadlines for filing court appeals. The appeals court said miners seeking benefits `` have encountered enormous frustration in the processing of their claims due to administrative delays and determinations under improper standards. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has repeatedly attempted to ease the burden of proof of disability and to expedite black lung claims.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the ruling would force the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> `` to embark on a potentially enormous reopening of closed cases that will impose a massive administrative burden. The records for approximately 94,000 claims would have to be retrieved and analyzed'' if the appeals court ruling were to apply nationwide. The 8th Circuit court has jurisdiction in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has created a special fund to pay off claims for miners with black lung disease, also known as pneumonconiosis. Coal mine operators owe the government some $ 3 billion that has been loaned to the fund from the federal treasury. The operators said the 8th Circuit court ruling, if applied nationwide, could burden the industry with $ 13.6 billion in additional payments. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> `` will be required to borrow the money to pay these claims until the coal industry is able to do so, if that day ever comes.'' In another dispute over black lung benefits, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in December made it easier for mining companies to block the award of some disability benefits. That decision upheld a <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> rule that miners are not entitled to an interim presumption they were disabled by the disease based on a single piece of medical evidence. The cases acted on today are <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Sebben </PERSON>, 87-821, and <PERSON> Whitfield </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Sebben </PERSON>, 87-827.
