<HEAD>Koalas Face Extinction, Expert Warns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The koala, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s national symbol, could become extinct unless long-term plans are devised to protect its habitat, an expert on the cuddly marsupials warned Monday. `` I am positive that if we do n't take immediate action the koala, our famous ` animal ambassador,' will slowly but surely slide down the inevitable path toward extinction,'' said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Koala </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. He told a three-day koala symposium at <ORGANIZATION> Melbourne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> extinction was only a matter of time as urban development erodes the creature's natural habitat. Koalas are found only on the eastern coast of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. They survive on a species of gum leaf and in recent years a venereal infection has devastated koala colonies. It is generally acknowleged that koalas were more prevalent prior to European settlement of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> in 1788, but no figures are available on their number today.
