<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand a ruling that drastically limits the power of communities to regulate cable television and raises doubts about the constitutionality of a key federal law governing cable operations. The court, citing a lack of jurisdiction, turned away an appeal by two <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> cities barred from enforcing public access and other rules challenged by a cable operator. The court's action, which appears to have been based on narrow procedural grounds, leaves open the possibility of a subsequent appeal. The dispute was between officials of <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Atherton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the cable operator. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> ruled last September that cable regulations adopted by the cities unconstitutionally violated <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION>'s free-speech rights. He threw out regulations that required Century Federal: _ To provide public access channels for those not connected with the cable company _ To wire the entire community to make service available to all residents _ To use a `` state-of-the-art'' system to keep pace with the latest technological advances The judge, who previously had ordered city officials to award an operating license to Century Federal, called for further hearings to study franchise fee requirements adopted by the cities. Palo Alto and <PERSON> Atherton </PERSON> officials said the ruling appears to declare unconstitutional a 1984 federal law regulating cable TV, even though the judge did not say in so many words he was invalidating the law. Although <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> `` purported not to decide the constitutionality of any provision of the act, -LRB- his -RRB- decision in fact holds that numerous sections of that statute are unconstitutional,'' lawyers for the cities said. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, in a `` friend-of-the-court'' legal brief filed by <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers, urged the court to deny the cities' appeal. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a 1986 ruling that has some bearing on the case acted on today, raised the possibility that communities may be barred from granting exclusive cable TV franchises. The court said cable franchise activities `` plainly implicate First Amendment interests.'' But the justices stopped short of a definitive ruling on the constitutional rights of cable operators. The ruling was in contrast to earlier decisions denying a constitutional right to operate over-the-air television or radio stations. Many cities award exclusive cable franchises city-wide or for various regions within the city. They also impose rules similar to those adopted by <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Atherton </PERSON>. The case is <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION> vs. Century Federal, 87-946.
