<HEAD>Parents Say Students Should Wear Identification Badges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some parents of students at a school where three faculty members were shot want students to wear identification badges and be subject to random searches with hand-held metal detectors. `` We're feeling as though some of -LRB- the school's -RRB- rules and regulations need to be looked at,'' said <PERSON> Ivy </PERSON> <PERSON> Villafana </PERSON>, whose daughter attends <ORGANIZATION> Pinellas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. `` If we can not have these metal detectors, then we can have doors that lock from the outside.'' About 50 parents met Sunday night to discuss ways to prevent further violence at the school. They plan to submit their ideas to the <ORGANIZATION> Pinellas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> during its regular meeting Wednesday. School officials were not invited to Sunday's meeting, but representatives from the school's Parent-Teacher-Student Association were on hand. On Feb. 11 two administrators and one student teacher were wounded in an altercation with two students. Assistant Principal <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> died of his injuries Wednesday. At the meeting, one woman favored providing the school resource officer _ a <LOCATION> Pinellas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> police officer assigned to the school _ with a hand-held metal detector. The officer should make random searches, she said. `` Does n't have to be a reason. Just stop them and run them up and down,'' she said. Principal <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Heminger </PERSON> declined to comment specifically on any of the group's suggestions. She said she was glad to hear the meeting was positive, `` and I hope that from -LRB- the meeting -RRB- come some good things that we can work with.'' One of the two students accused in the shootings had recently been suspended for cursing a teacher. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Leotti </PERSON>, organizer of Sunday night's meeting, told parents that other school systems she surveyed around the country send students to counselors before suspending them. She will suggest Wednesday that <LOCATION> Pinellas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> institute a similar policy. `` We want suspensions, but we want counseling,'' Ms. <PERSON> Villafana </PERSON> said. `` And we do n't mean guidance counselors, we mean psychologists.'' If a student uses profanity when expressing frustration to a teacher, he should n't be suspended, she said. Among the other suggestions: providing counseling for teachers and students; having a substitute resource officer when the regular officer is out; providing new carpeting to replace one with bloodstains; having a crisis-intervention team; and having a parent volunteer force patrolling hallways.
