<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Angie </PERSON> <PERSON> Debo </PERSON>, who came to <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> by covered wagon and became known as `` The First Lady of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> History </LOCATION>,'' has died at age 98. Ms. <PERSON> Debo </PERSON>, of <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, died Sunday at an Enid hospital, said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindholm </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Abernathy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Funeral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Crescent </LOCATION>. The nationally esteemed historian wrote 13 books and hundreds of articles about Indian and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> history. Last month, Gov. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellmon </PERSON> presented her with the 1987 Award for Scholarly Distinction from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. In a new forward she wrote at age 91 for her 1949 book `` <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, Foot-Loose and Fancy-Free,'' Ms. <PERSON> Debo </PERSON> called her home `` more than just another state.'' `` It is a lens in which the long rays of time are focused into the brightest of light,'' she wrote. `` In its magnifying clarity, dim facets of the American character stand more clearly revealed. For in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> all the experiences that went into the making of the nation have been speeded up. Here all the American traits have been intensified. The one who can interpret <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> can grasp the meaning of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in the modern world.'' Her books include `` The Rise and Fall of the <LOCATION> Choctaw </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>,'' `` And Still The Waters Run,'' `` Geronimo: The Man, His Time, His Place'' and `` Prairie City.'' In 1985, her portrait was hung permanently in the rotunda of the state Capitol, near portraits <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorpe </PERSON>, and <LOCATION> Sequoyah </LOCATION>. She earned the <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunning </PERSON> Prize of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Alfred </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Knopf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fellowship </ORGANIZATION> in history. A one-hour documentary on her life and work is scheduled to be broadcast next fall as part of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The American Experience'' series. A funeral was scheduled for Wednesday, <PERSON> Lindholm </PERSON> said, adding that she had no surviving relatives.
