<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it will judge the validity of a federal law that lets independent counsels investigate alleged crimes by high-ranking executive branch officials. The court also rejected the latest appeal of one target of such an investigation _ Marine Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>. The court's decision, expected by July, will resolve a major constitutional dispute and will affect the criminal conviction of former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> and the rejuvenated investigation of <ORGANIZATION> ex-Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>. The decision also could affect other investigations by special prosecutors appointed under the law. The justices allowed special prosecutor <PERSON> Alexia </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> to resume her investigation of <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, raising the possibility that grand jury indictments could be handed down before the high court's ruling A federal appeals court ruled that the Watergate-era law creating independent counsels impermissibly gives presidential appointment powers to the federal courts. The appeals court had derailed <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>'s investigation. A three-judge panel of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> ruled, by a 2-1 vote last month, that the independent counsel provisions of the Ethics in Government Act of 1978 were an unconstitutional encroachment of the exclusive power of the president to enforce criminal laws. Under the law, a special court appoints ind