<HEAD>Expulsion is Only Appropriate Sanction for Biaggi, Committee Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s violation of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ethics constituted `` criminal conduct of a most serious nature going to the heart of his representational responsibilities'' and warranted expulsion, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Official </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conduct </ORGANIZATION> said in a report released Monday. The committee, which recommended Thursday that <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, be expelled from the seat he has held for 20 years, explained why it had elected to exercise its most serious punishment. `` The facts and circumstances giving rise to the violations, being of the most serious nature, warrant the imposition of the most stringent sanction available to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>,'' the 148-page report said. `` Accordingly, the committee submits that expulsion is the only sanction appropriate to the violations committed by Representative <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> was not in his office Monday, but he said Thursday that he intended to vigorously fight the expulsion recommendation. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, 70, was convicted in September of illegally accepting a paid <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> vacation from <PERSON> Meade </PERSON> <PERSON> Esposito </PERSON>, the former <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, Democratic leader. <PERSON> Esposito </PERSON> was seeking government help for Coastal Dry Dock and <ORGANIZATION> Repair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a financially troubled <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> shipyard that owed $ 280,000 in premiums to <PERSON> Esposito </PERSON>'s insurance brokerage firm. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> was also convicted of illegally crossing state lines to accept the gratuity and obstructing justice by trying to influence how <PERSON> Esposito </PERSON> answered the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s questions. He was sentenced to 2 -LCB- years in prison and a $ 500,000 fine, and is free pending appeal. The ethics committee concluded that <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> violated rules against discrediting the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>; accepting impermissible gifts from a person or organization with a direct or indirect interest in legislation; failing to report a gift worth $ 250 or more on his financial disclosure form; and accepting a favor or benefit that might be construed as influencing the performance of government duties. After reviewing evidence from <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s trial, the committee `` found that the offenses for which Representative <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> was convicted involved criminal conduct of a most serious nature going to the heart of his representational responsibilities.'' The committee's resolution to expel <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> must be approved by two-thirds of the 435-member House to take effect. The matter may be taken up on the floor at any time, now that the committee report has been released. If the resolution passes, <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> would be the second congressman expelled from the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> since the Civil War. Rep. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> `` Ozzie'' <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, D-Pa., was ousted in 1980 after his conviction in the Abscam bribery scheme The committee report also includes a transcript of its closed Dec. 17, 1987, meeting, at which <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> pleaded for leniency and declared, `` I am incorruptible.'' <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> argued that the vacation he took, at a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> health spa, was `` hospitality'' from <PERSON> Esposito </PERSON>, a friend of 40 years, not a gratuity. Placing the value of the vacation at about $ 3,000, <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> asked rhetorically, `` <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> is going to compromise himself for $ 3,000? I would n't compromise myself for $ 100,000.'' <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> also said he did not know that <PERSON> Esposito </PERSON> had business with Coastal until a bugged telephone conversation on June 2, 1986, more than a year after the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> vacation.
