<HEAD>Senate Asked to Ratify Law Enforcement Treaty With Canada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> asked the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Monday to ratify a treaty with <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> that he said should help the two countries prosecute terrorists, drug traffickers and other criminals. The Treaty on Mutual Legal Assistance in Criminal Matters was signed by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Canadian Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> at their meeting in <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, on March 18, 1985. The White House said submission was delayed while annexes to the pact were worked out by the two nations. It is one of a series of such legal assistance treaties being negotiated by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Similar pacts have gone into force with <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. Others have been signed but not yet gone into force with <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION> on behalf of the <LOCATION> Cayman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sent the treaty with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for consideration just before his meeting with Mexican President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Mazatlan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, on Feb. 13. In his message to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, he said the treaty with <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> `` should be an effective tool to prosecute a wide variety of modern criminals including members of drug cartels, ` white-collar criminals' and terrorists.'' The treaty provides for the two countries to assist each other in taking testimony or statements of witnesses; providing documents, records and evidence; executing requests for searches and seizures and serving documents. It also provides for assistance in proceedings relating to forfeiture of the proceeds of crime, restitution for victims and collection of fines.
