<HEAD>27 People Killed In Two Days Despite State of Siege Emergency
Measures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers, guerrillas and a communist leader were killed Monday despite emergency measures to curb one of the bloodiest spates of violence the country has seen in three decades. Ten peasants were singled out at a cockfight Sunday and shot by men wearing black hoods, official reports said. In all, 27 people have been killed in ambushes and assassinations over two days. President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> last month ordered a state of emergency in an attempt to halt a wave of violence that has taken the lives of more than 1,700 people in the last year. More than 120 people have been killed this year. Most of those deaths came after <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> ordered army troops to reinforce the police and increased jail terms for many violent crimes, especially those committed by drug traffickers, leftist guerrillas and paid assassins. Leftist guerrillas on Monday released seven mayors and two reporters kidnapped earlier this month, the radio stations RCN and <PERSON> Caracol </PERSON> said. Last week the rebels freed four mayors and a reporter they had abducted. The guerrillas warned the mayors to budget more money to help the poor and said they planned to blow up the country's main oil pipeline again to keep oil from being exported. All 11 mayors and three reporters kidnapped were from towns in northeast <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and all had been held for about a week. The kidnappings were by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, known as the <ORGANIZATION> ELN </ORGANIZATION>, which follows the political ideology of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>. The rebel group has blown up the country's main oil pipeline 13 times since Jan. 12. The latest victim of an apparent right wing death squad was <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonima </PERSON>, a communist leader and assistant city attorney in the northwest city of <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>. A man riding on a motorcycle Monday shot and killed <PERSON> Gonima </PERSON> and wounded his driver as <PERSON> Gonima </PERSON> headed for work at city hall, the national police said in a news release. <PERSON> Gonima </PERSON> was a member of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION>, which has seen more than 500 of its members killed since it was organized by former guerrillas in 1985. Leftist guerrillas ambushed an army patrol Monday, killing four soldiers, the press office for the government of the state of <LOCATION> Antioquia </LOCATION> said in a news release. In southwest <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> guerrillas attacked the towns of Trujillo and <LOCATION> Caloto </LOCATION> on Sunday and killed seven policemen, the army's <ORGANIZATION> 8th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brigade </ORGANIZATION> said in a communique. Near Vistahermosa, in a jungled area in the southeast state of <LOCATION> Meta </LOCATION>, 20 men wearing black hoods and carrying submachine guns surrounded dozens of men attending a cockfight on Sunday, the police said. Ten peasants were separated from the group and and shot as they pleaded for their lives, the policer said. The police report did not say who was suspected in the massacre. Drug traffickers have long dominated large areas of the vast jungles in eastern <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. The traffickers kill people they suspect of being informers or for refusing to let traffickers use their land for growing coca trees, the source for cocaine. A broadcast reporter and a mother and her 15-month-old girl were killed Sunday when gunmen opened fire on the reporter's car as the three traveled along a highway near the western city of <LOCATION> Cali </LOCATION>, the national police there said in a news release. The reporter, <PERSON> Belisario </PERSON> <PERSON> Zambrano </PERSON>, of the Cali station <ORG