<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A contingency plan to help prevent an uncontrolled meltdown of the financial markets won the endorsement Monday of the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and three other representatives. `` Our markets remain vibrant, but they are at the same time delicate,'' Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., wrote in a letter to the heads of three regulatory agencies `` To permit them to function without such a contingency plan courts unnecessary risk.'' The letter was also signed by Reps. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications and finance subcommittee; <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Lent </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, ranking minority member on the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Rinaldo </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.J. </LOCATION>, ranking minority member of the finance subcommittee The letter to the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> was prompted by the Oct. 19 stock crash. `` The market decline ... was a wrenching and sobering experience for the marketplace, market participants, regulators and those of us in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> with oversight responsibilities for our securities markets,'' the let