<HEAD>Reagan Cautions Governors Against Costly Moves On Welfare</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new graf 17, ``Rep. Tom ...'', to UPDATE with
reaction; picks up old graf 17, ``Illinois Gov. ...''; ADDS one
graf with Captain Kangaroo.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> cautioned the nation's governors Monday against pressing for costly federal solutions to the problems of welfare and child care His remarks to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> were labeled a disappointment by <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, a Democratic presidential hopeful, who said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> should be backing the governors' bipartisan welfare reform bill in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> instead said he still strongly supports a less costly Republican alternative that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rejected two months ago. He also cautioned the governors to go slow on the issue of child care, where both Democrats and Republicans in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are proposing to expand federal support and subsidies for working parents. `` Maybe it's my conservative bent, but I ca n't help but feel uneasy sometimes,'' he told the governors gathered in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Room </LOCATION> of the White House. Welfare programs have become `` a crippling poverty trap. ... They keep the poor poor,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` Now, much of the push for child care is designed to rectify the ills of earlier programs, and many of these efforts are timely and good. But in this area, more than any other, government should tread carefully.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the alternative bill sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., would also give states freedom to `` develop your own ideas on child care. Afterwards, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told reporters that he was very disappointed. `` Just one word from the president, I think, would get this bill passed and done before the election, and get it off the table as a partisan issue and get going,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` He keeps telling us stories about <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, and we're trying to explain to him that the vast majority of people on welfare these days are single mothers with young children, and it's a combination of real training for real jobs, combined with day care, that makes a difference,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s chief of staff, said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would veto the House-passed welfare reform bill, but might approve a less expensive measure still being shaped by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The governors are pushing Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>'s bill, which would toughen enforcement of child support, help states pay for job training and make participation mandatory for most unemployed adults. It would also provide some transitional Medicaid and welfare benefits for families exiting the relief rolls for work. <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Democrat, has 56 co-sponsors for his bill, which would cost $ 2.3 billion over five years, compared to the $ 4.3 billion <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill, which would raise benefits and prohibit states from denying welfare to families with both parents in the home. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> bill is not yet satisfactory, but he held out the hope that <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., might be able to fashion a compromise satisfactory to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, has not introduced an alternative bill. <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> said in a telephone interview he heard two messages from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>: `` One says that we're going to veto the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill. The other says we can try to work something out. I choose to respond to the second message. There's too much at stake here. If the president is interested in the subject, I'll be happy to work with Sen. <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> on anything.'' Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who spearheaded passage of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill, said in an interview, `` The time to do something about welfare is now and the only person who seems opposed to it or looking at the past is the president. We're not going to end child poverty by leaving it to the states to do it. They do n't have the money.'' Illinois Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, a Republican, told reporters, `` I think there's just a fundamental disagreement about how far to go on welfare reform, especially with regard to cost. The governors changed their mind, not the president.'' But despite that sticking point, <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said, `` I still hold out hope that between the administration and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> we'll get a bill.'' <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON>, a Democrat who is leading the governors' push for welfare reform, emerged from the meeting and said he felt <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was open to compromise. `` I am encouraged because basically their negotiating strategy with everybody always is to take the hardest possible line and then come off of it at the end,'' <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> said. In the private meeting that followed <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s speech, <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> said, `` I told him we thought his bill was not a good bill and that we were willing to make some changes in what came out of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, but we were n't going to get anywhere if his emissary kept saying, ` Well, we're going to veto whatever passes that we do n't like.'' <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> replied that `` he heard us ... and was willing to work with us, so I think that's good.'' <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, a Republican, said he shared <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s misgivings about the House-passed welfare bill He said it `` might really compound the problem'' by increasing federal funding without giving states more control over welfare rules. What the states need is flexibility to allow them to `` gradually remove -LRB- people -RRB- from welfare'' instead of terminating their benefits as soon as they get a job, <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> said. Later, the governors' committee on human resources heard television's Captain Kangaroo, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Keeshan </PERSON>, plead for corporations to start providing quality day care. `` I'm almost ashamed at times to be an American,'' the children's performer and advocate said. `` We are half a century behind in addressing day care. We are going to pay an enormous price a quarter-century down the line.''
