<HEAD>Nunn: INF Pact Faces Thorough Senate Review Before Ratification
Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocaited Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said Monday the new U.S.-Soviet nuclear arms control treaty wo n't be ratified until after his <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> the panel finishes its line-by-line examination of the pact. That laborious process began Monday after the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sent the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> 31 volumes of documents involved in the long negotiations which led to the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces -LRB- INF -RRB- pact. `` It is very regrettable that we have to go through this,'' said the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> Democrat, who emerged victorious in a fight with the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration over the legal meaning of treaties. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, chairman of the armed services panel, said he did n't know how long it would take the committee to finish its work. The panel is one of three <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committees considering the treaty, which was signed in December by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Ratification by the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which requires a two-thirds vote, is expected later. The INF fight was based on a previous dispute between the Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration over the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Star Wars anti-missile program. A number of Star Wars tests would be banned unless the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> moved from the current `` narrow'' interpretation of the ABM treaty to a `` broad'' view. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration had asserted it was n't bound by what previous administrations told <ORGANIZATION> Congres