<HEAD>Greek and Turkish Cypriot Leaders Spar on Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 6th graf ``Vassiliou, a...'' to UPDATE
with Reagan congratulatory message and planned response. Pickup 7th
graf pvs ``Denktash proposed...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICK LUDINGTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>' Greek and Turkish leaders sparred Monday only a day after elections, with the Turkish head proposing talks in neutral territory and the Greek president-elect insisting they be held on his own turf. The dispute over a matter of protocol disappointed some who had for a new start in talks to reunify <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> in a federation. The sparring began when <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Rauf </PERSON> <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> invited Greek Cypriot president-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> to informal talks on the future of the island, to be held in a neutral area. <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> countered with an invitation to <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> `` to come and see me at the presidential palace.'' `` I am the elected president of the <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> and in that capacity I would be most happy to welcome Mr. <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> as the leader of the Turkish Cypriot community,'' <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> said in a radio interview. <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> is president of the breakaway <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, which was proclaimed in 1983 and is internationally recognized only by <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. He does not recognize <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON>, who will be sworn in next Sunday, as president of all <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON>, a millionaire businessman backed by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, defeated veteran right-wing politician <PERSON> Glafcos </PERSON> <PERSON> Clerides </PERSON> in general elections Sunday. Only Greek Cypriots voted. An official announcement said President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sent <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> a message of congratulations, expressing the wish to continue relations with <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. `` I look forward, through you, to continuing the friendly relations between our two countries, a relationship which has been characterized by a special warmth and a constant effort to build mutual respect and understanding,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s message said. `` I know that you have the determination to make the effort to bring about the lasting peace which has so long escaped the people of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>,'' the message said. <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> said he will thank <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in a message expressing hope the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will more actively to persuade <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> to withdraw its troops. <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> proposed in his invitation to <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> that the talks be held at the <ORGANIZATION> Ledra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters on the Green Line dividing Turkish and Greek Cypriots. He said the meeting `` would be between the leaders of the two politically equal parties or between the presidents of two equal political entities.'' <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> had said during his campaign that he was willing to meet with the Turkish Cypriots without preconditions. But his counter-offer to meet <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> at the presidential palace in the Greek Cypriot-controlled zone, citing his own role as president of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> only as leader of the Turkish Cypriot community, was certain to be rebuffed. In the interview with the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> indicated no new flexibility in the conflict between <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> and Turkish Cypriots. He accused <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> of building up its military presence in the Turkish Cypriot zone in northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> since the 1974 invasion which partitioned the island. The invasion followed a coup by Greek Cypriot extremists aimed at uniting the entire island with <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. `` The realities of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> are that in these years, <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, instead of recucing its military presence here, has been building it up in every way,'' he said. He also accused <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> of bringing in 40,000 to 50,000 Turkish settlers to beef up the Turkish Cypriot minority, which numbered 120,000 at the time of the invasion. The Greek Cypriot population is more than 500,000. After election results were announced early Monday, <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> said he would work for the withdrawal of Turkish troops and settlers, but woud try to achieve a spirit of rapprochement with the Turkish Cypriots. Greek-Turkish negotiations have been stalled since President <PERSON> Spyros </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyprianou </PERSON>, who lost a bid for a third term in the first round of elections Feb. 14, rejected proposals for a two-zone federation proposed by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. The proposals had been accepted by <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON>, who now insists upon them as the basis for restarting talks. <PERSON> Kyprianou </PERSON> had insisted that before any talks began on a federation, all Turkish troops must withdraw and the Turks must allow <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cypriot </ORGANIZATION> refugees, who fled after the 1974 invasion, to return to their homes in the north. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> proposals suggested that talks on troop withdrawal and the `` right of return'' would be discussed by committees simultaneously with talks on the nature of the federation.
