<HEAD>Dinner at a Cooperative Gives Shultz a Taste of Soviet Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> tasted the fruits of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms first-hand Monday as he hosted a candlelit dinner at a cooperative restaurant that was once a money-losing bar. The red-brick Skazka -LRB- `` Fairy Tale'' -RRB- restaurant off southeastern <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Taganka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> would have been illegal before last year's decision by Soviet authorities to loosen laws governing individual labor and cooperative ownership. `` As soon as we heard they were authorizing cooperatives, we decided to start one,'' said <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kutuzov </PERSON>, the head of the nine-member collective that runs the <LOCATION> Skazka </LOCATION>. The restaurant, which can seat 34 customers in its upstairs dining room, opened April 1 last year. Its hearty Russian fare swiftly made it so popular with Muscovites and foreign residents that profits soared to as much as $ 23,300 a month, <PERSON> Kutuzov </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Skazka </PERSON>'s friendly waitresses and prompt service are in stark contrast to the situation that prevails at most of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s state-owned restaurants, where customers sometimes wait for hours before being served Cooperatives are also more expensive than state-run restaurants, which has led some Soviets to oppose them as socially unjust. The dinner menu offered <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> cost between $ 25 and $ 33 per person, <PERSON> Kutuzov </PERSON> said, compared to an average of $ 3 to $ 8 for an evening meal in a government-owned restaurant. A table piled with sturgeon in aspic, pickled vegetables inside a pumpkin, bottles of mineral water and grapes was set out for <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, who had finished two days of talks in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with top Soviet officials, including <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader. <PERSON> Skazka </PERSON>'s chefs also prepared homemade noodle soup with mushrooms, a cabbage soup called `` shchi,'' stuffed pork cutlets, dumplings with mushroom and chicken and small Russian pancakes. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, who was accompanied by his wife <PERSON> Helena </PERSON> and <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Matlock </PERSON>, met in the dining room with some of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s top cultural figures and intellectuals, including cinematographer <PERSON> Elem </PERSON> <PERSON> Klimov </PERSON>, playwright <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Shatrov </PERSON>, economist <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Shmelov </PERSON> and writer <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Soloukhin </PERSON>. Reporters briefly allowed into the wood-paneled room before <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> arrived spotted one apparent concession to the VIP guests _ bottles of Georgian and French wines set out on a table. As a cooperative, the Skazka normally does not have the right to serve alcohol. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said in mid-January that 13,000 co-ops had been established in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He said more than 300,000 people were working for themselves within guidelines set by the government to encourage better services and goods than those provided by the state-run sector. The venture has been a clear success for the nine people who put up a total of $ 5,000 to launch the Skazka. Last month <PERSON> Kutuzov </PERSON>, chairman of the Skazka cooperative, took home $ 1,050, more than three times the average Soviet wage of $ 330. The building that now contains the restaurant was once a bar favored by `` Lyubers,'' body-building enthusiasts from a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> suburb that some press reports have said prey on long-haired Soviet youths who like Western rock music. Either because of its tough clientele, or because the health-conscious <PERSON> Lyubers </PERSON> did not drink enough alcohol, the bar lost money, <PERSON> Kutuzov </PERSON> said. Now its clientele has radically changed, with foreigners making up as much as 90 percent of the dinner customers on a given evening, <PERSON> Kutuzov </PERSON> said.
