> Kalish </PERSON> began his career in drug trafficking at an early age, his friends say. The son of a mid-level <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> executive who died in 1980, <PERSON> Kalish </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and grew up in <LOCATION> Bellaire </LOCATION>, a comfortable suburb of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> DeGuerin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Kalish </PERSON> was already selling marijuana when he dropped out of the 11th grade. `` I do n't believe he ever had a straight job,'' said <PERSON> DeGuerin </PERSON>. By age 27, <PERSON> Kalish </PERSON> had been indicted twice in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> for trying to import 140,000 pounds of marijuana in two loads nine days apart in December 1979. The second seizure _ 100,000 pounds _ was then the largest ever in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kalish </PERSON> eventually fled, assumed a new identity and in 1983 settled in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, where he worked with <PERSON> Ritch </PERSON>, says Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kalish </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ritch </PERSON> set up a smuggling organization and a sophisticated nationwide distribution network that made more than $ 200 million in four years. The Kalish-Ritch organization began to fall apart when the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> arrested <PERSON> Kalish </PERSON> on July 26, 1984, as he was boarding a chartered <ORGANIZATION> Lear </ORGANIZATION> jet under an assumed name at <ORGANIZATION> Tampa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION>.
