<HEAD>Nofziger Attorneys Try To Overturn Guilty Verdict, Get New Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>'s defense attorneys filed motions Monday to set aside the former presidential aide's illegal lobbying convictions on the grounds that prosecutors failed to prove he violated the law. The defense also filed a motion for a new trial, contending that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flannery </PERSON> erroneously instructed jurors about determining whether the issues <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> lobbied about were of `` direct and substantial'' interest to the White House. <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>, 63, was convicted Feb. 11 of three counts of illegally lobbying former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> colleagues on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a maritime engineers union and the manufacturer of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> A-10 anti-tank plane. The former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> political director faces a potential two-year prison term and a $ 10,000 fine for each of the three convictions. He is scheduled to be sentenced March 25. In its motions in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, the defense repeated contentions made throughout the four-week trial that the prosecution team headed by independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> failed to prove that the issues <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> raised with former colleagues were `` particular matters'' of `` direct and substantial interest'' to the White House. `` The gross insufficiency of the evidence mandates that the guilty verdict ... against Mr. <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> b set aside and that a judgment of acquittal be entered,'' defense lawyer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> and <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Barcella </PERSON> said in their pleadings. In asking for a new trial, the defense said the definition of `` direct and substantial interest'' that <PERSON> Flannery </PERSON> gave the jury during final instructions `` clearly encompassed interest well beyond the scope of the statute.'' This instruction allowed jurors to confuse the `` personal interest of certain representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'' with `` direct and substantial'' interest, the defense said. For instance, references in testimony to <PERSON> Pier </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Talenti </PERSON>, a volunteer on <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>'s White House staff who visited <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s plant, might be the only basis for the jury to conclude the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had an interest in <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>'s bid for a military engine contract, the defense said. Although he was not called as a witness, <PERSON> Talenti </PERSON> was described by a former <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> executive as expressing interest in the company's bid for a contract to build small engines for the Army in 1981. An Army procurement official also testified that <PERSON> Talenti </PERSON> urged consideration of <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>'s bid that year. The defense said <PERSON> Flannery </PERSON>'s `` internally inconsistent and confusing'' instruction `` failed adequately to explain the comparative and relative importance of a matter to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, and it did not instruct the jury to place that interest in its proper context.'' <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>, who left the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in early 1982, was convicted, among other things, for sending an April 8, 1982, memo to then-presidential counselor <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> urging support for <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to persuade reluctant <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> officials to award the $ 32 million contract. `` The very purpose of the communication to Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was to create and stimulate interest, a contact that is not prohibited'' by the law, the defense said. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, now attorney general, testified at the trial that he could n't recall receiving <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>'s note, which suggested he enlist the support of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and other top administration officials.
