<HEAD>Firefighters Continue to Call in Sick</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 All firefighters scheduled to work Monday night's shift joined scores of other colleagues in calling in sick, leaving <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>'s fire protection to 87 firefighters who have been on duty around the clock since Friday. Meanwhile, a <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge delayed ruling on the city's request for contempt citations against 110 firefighters who called in sick over the weekend in defiance of a back-to-work order Judge <PERSON> Americo </PERSON> <PERSON> Campanella </PERSON> gave union president <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> until 10 a.m. Tuesday to inform all 450 members of the union that they must to return to work under the temporary restraining order issued Saturday by another judge. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> was also ordered to furnish a list of all firefighters who had called in sick over the weekend and outline the nature of their illness or the illness of family members they said they were staying home to care for. City officials went from home to home Monday leaving notices for firefighters of the contempt hearing. <PERSON> Campanella </PERSON> indicated his decision to put off ruling on the matter hinged on the relatively low number of firefighters contacted either by the city or <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. The union represents 450 of the city's total uniformed force of 479. <PERSON> Campanella </PERSON> indicated his decision to put off ruling on the matter hinged on the relatively low number of firefighters contacted either by the city or <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, a fire captain, denies the union orchestrated any sickout. If found to be a job action as <PERSON> Moise </PERSON> and city officials assert, the sickout would be illegal under <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> law. The dispute apparently concerns language in a contract ratified by firefighters in December that the city has yet to sign. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said the city is trying to renege on a provision that calls for an officer to be placed in charge of each rescue unit. Union members also complain that promises to replacement worn-out or damaged equipment like boots, helmets and firecoats have not been fulfilled. All but one of the 51 firefighters scheduled to report for work at 8 a.m. Saturday called in sick Friday, said Fire Chief <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moise </PERSON>. An additional 60 called in sick for the shift that was supposed to begin at 6 a.m. Sunday, <PERSON> Moise </PERSON> said. Assistant Fire Chief <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> told <PERSON> Campanella </PERSON> that all of the firefighters scheduled to report at 6 p.m. Monday had called in sick. `` I have nobody coming in,'' <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> testified. The union represents 450 of the city's total uniformed force of 479. The firefighters, divided into four platoons, work two 10-hour days and two 12-hour days, then are off four days. <PERSON> Moise </PERSON> said the 87 firefighters in the platoon that has been kept on duty since Friday evening will stay on the job until the issue is resolved. The chief testified the average absentee level is seven to eight firefighters for any particular shift. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> agreed the number of sick firefighters was `` unusually high.'' Most of the people he contacted after the restraining order was issued said either they or someone in their family had a 24-hour virus, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said he called in sick because his mother, who has heart trouble, also had the flu. <PERSON> Ragosta </PERSON> tried to show the sickout presented a danger to the public health and safety. <PERSON> Moise </PERSON> said he was becoming concerned that fatigue among firefighters on the job since Friday might affect their ability to operate sophisticated equipment and their response time in a crisis. He said the sickout was costing $ 20,000 a day in overtime and related expenses.
