<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Sexton </PERSON>'s reward for winning a school contest was nothing to snort at. Then again, it probably did n't make him squeal with delight <PERSON> Sexton </PERSON>, a history teacher and wrestling coach at <ORGANIZATION> Wilmington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, came in first in a school project to raise money for Children's Hospital in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>. His payoff _ he had to kiss a pig. He put his mouth where the smart money was, planting a kiss on the snout of a pig during a pep rally Friday while the students and faculty watched. <PERSON> Sexton </PERSON> won a contest in which students and teachers put money in gallon milk jugs as their way of choosing a sow smoocher. There were 45 teachers up for votes, which cost 25 cents to cast, said home economics teacher <PERSON> Bonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>. The contest, dubbed `` Squeal of Fortune,'' raised nearly $ 250.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Auburn </ORGANIZATION> residents better not plan to serve pie this weekend _ not with a horde of Curly, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> and <PERSON> Moe </PERSON> fans headed their way. Three Stooges aficionados from throughout the nation are expected to converge on this central <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> city to share recollections of the zany antics that entertained generations of moviegoers and television viewers. The two-day convention, which begins Saturday, will feature about 30 dealers in Stooges memorabilia, imitators of the threesome and, of course, a pie fight. `` They kind of created the pie fight,'' said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Eugley </PERSON>, the convention organizer. `` In about a quarter of their shorts, there's somebody getting a pie in the face. <PERSON> Eugley </PERSON>, a 36-year-old salesman from <ORGANIZATION> Auburn </ORGANIZATION>, said the convention has been promoted in the national magazine published by the Three Stooges fan club and is expected to draw more than 700 fans. The convention will be addressed by telephone by <PERSON> Emil </PERSON> <PERSON> Sitka </PERSON>, a supporting actor for the Stooges who is writing a book about the late comics. Stooges movies will be shown throughout the convention, <PERSON> Eugley </PERSON> said, including some never seen by the general public. `` Curly was married four times _ he had quite the thing for women _ and we'll have some films of his weddings,'' <PERSON> Eugley </PERSON> said. He said convention-goers will also see films of Moe Howard entertaining at a backyard barbecue. Proceeds from the convention will go to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, in part because <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> died of the disease.
