<HEAD>Report Near Collision Between Helicopter And Jet Fighter: Third in
Two Weeks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An oil rig helicopter and a Phantom jet fighter came within a half-mile of colliding over the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> on Monday, according to the helicopter firm. It was the third reported near-miss in two weeks in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s crowded skies. The earlier incidents involved jetliners carrying hundreds of passengers and prompted calls for an inquiry into growing air congestion before the summer travel season begins. The government on Monday accused air traffic controllers of fomenting `` public hysteria'' and said there was no cause for alarm. Bristow Helicopters said its <ORGANIZATION> Puma </ORGANIZATION> craft carrying 11 passengers and two crew members from an oil rig 165 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Aberdeen </LOCATION> climbed sharply as it neared the Scottish city after air traffic controllers warned that it was on a collision course with a <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> jet. <PERSON> Bristow </PERSON> said its helicopter moved up from an altitude of 2,000 feet and the Phantom passed below. Both aircraft landed safely and no one was reported injured. A Bristow spokesman said the helicopter pilot filed an `` air miss'' report with the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, or CAA. Earlier Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> promised an investigation into an incident Sunday involving a British Caledonian BA 1-11 and a Pan American <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727. <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> the jetliners came within 2,000 yards while flying over southern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> but he said they were not in danger of colliding. He said the number of near-misses had declined sharply in the last 10 years. `` We mus n't be complacent, neither must we overreact,'' he said. In the previous incident this month, a <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L1011 </ORGANIZATION> and a Balkan Bulgarian Tu 54 with a total of 543 people aboard narrowly avoided colliding. The <ORGANIZATION> CAA </ORGANIZATION> called that an `` exceptionally serious'' case and <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> said the authority took the unusual step of asking the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> to make an independent investigation. According to the <ORGANIZATION> CAA </ORGANIZATION>, the number of near-misses per 100,000 flying hours in British air space decreased from 6.2 in 1980 to 2.8 in 1986. It said there were 12 incidents involving serious risk last year, unchanged from 1986. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Stock </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s largest air traffic controllers' union, said the control system is nearly overloaded. `` The system is working at full blast,'' said <PERSON> Stock </PERSON>, head of the 1,500-member <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Controllers </ORGANIZATION>. `` If a mistake is made then there is very little room to maneuver.'' He said safety should improve when a new computer system is inaugurated in 1990 and a new control center in 1995. The guild has demanded increased manpower in the meantime, saying five job vacancies at the main control center in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Drayton </LOCATION> have not been filled since September. The <ORGANIZATION> CAA </ORGANIZATION> on Monday claimed the controllers were promoting public alarm to gain leverage in negotiations over working conditions, including the number of controllers on duty at peak times. `` The controllers are putting pressure on the <ORGANIZATION> CAA </ORGANIZATION> by harping on the subject of safety,'' said the authority spokesman who was not identified in line with government policy. `` Anonymous controllers are constantly feeding information engendering alarm and concern.''
