<HEAD>Navy Secretary Leaves with a Blast at His Boss</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``An administration ...'' to UPDATE
with Ball's likely nomination and Webb's resignation to be accepted
at White House Tuesday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> abruptly resigned Monday, accusing <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> of abandoning the <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s goal of a 600-ship <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and of demonstrating a lack of leadership and vision. `` This building needs to be led,'' <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said in telling reporters of his decision. `` It needs leadership. It needs some vision. I'm saying that if I had a piece of advice to give to Secretary <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, it would be to spend a lot more time with the top leaders in this building. `` He's been spending a lot of time with the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and a lot of time on the Hill. I think they -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> leaders -RRB- need to feel his vision and to understand what he believes in.'' <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>, 42, a highly decorated Marine veteran of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> combat and the author of the best-selling <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> war novel, `` Fields of Fire,'' left after only 10 months in his <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> position. He told President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in his resignation letter that the president could have realized his cherished goal of building a 600-ship fleet, were it not for <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>. An administration official who asked not to be identified said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> wants to recommend that <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, assistant to the president for legislative affairs, be nominated to replace <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>. The source said the White House probably would announce <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>'s nomination on Tuesday, at the same time it announces formal acceptance of <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>'s resignation. Talking to reporters, <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> accused <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> of ordering him to keep quiet about internal budget fighting, saying the defense chief had written him a note saying he should deny news stories reporting it was the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> _ and not the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> _ proposing to mothball ships. `` Now, I'm not going to deny the truth,'' <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> declined to respond to the criticism, issuing a written statement saying only that he had learned of <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>'s resignation decision `` with regret.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> added in a separate statement, however, that if <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> had decided he could not `` defend the department's decisions'' on the budget, then `` under the circumstances, he has done the honorable thing.'' White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said: `` Secretary <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> is having to make some very difficult adjustments in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> to accommodate budgetary reductions. Secretary <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> indicates he is unable to operate under these constraints, but I know the president feels he has given very valuable service to the country ...'' Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that oversees the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> budget, said in a statement: `` I'm sorry to see <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> go In his brief stint, he impressed the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> as an able secretary.'' `` Although I am not endorsing his views, his resignation has obviously launched an important new stage of the debate about <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> priorities and the size and type of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> we need.'' Three times, <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> developed a plan for cutting its fiscal 1989 budget in such a way that the goal of expanding the fleet to 600 ships could still be reached. And each time, he said, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s advice was `` ignored'' by <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>. `` I can only conclude that the decision to reduce the level of our fleet to a point that it may never reach the 600-ship goal was motivated by other than military and strategic reasoning,'' <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> wrote <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> and others have argued that 600 ships were the minimum needed for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> to meet its worldwide commitments. Since his recommendations `` were rejected by your secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION>, I am unable to support him personally or to defend this amended budget during budget deliberations -LRB- in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said. `` Consequently, I find it necessary to resign from my position as ecretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>'s decision to step down surprised <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials alike. He assumed the post only last April, seven months before <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> succeeded <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, like all the services, was ordered in early December to slash its fiscal 1989 budget proposal to comply with a new deficit-reduction plan. Ultimately, <PERSON> Webb </PERS