<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge on Monday dismissed a lawsuit challenging the constitutionality of new sentencing guidelines, ruling that two public defender offices lacked legal standing to bring the case. The decision by U.S. District Judge <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON> dismissed the case on technical grounds. It came four days after two federal judges in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> had held the new sentencing guidelines were unconstitutional. The two judges in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> ruled that the 1984 law establishing the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Sentencing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> was unconstitutional because it improperly placed the panel in the judicial instead of the executive branch in violation of the constitution's separation-of-powers doctrine Unlike the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> cases, the suit before <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON> did not involve defendants who faced sentencing under the new guidelines, which provide a complicated set of factors for determining the length of a defendant's incarceration. <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON> found that federal public defenders' offices in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> lacked legal standing to sue because they could n't show they were harmed by the new sentencing guidelines. `` Permitting lawyers to sue without clients, or at best, with only potential clients, merely because their putatative clients allegedly will be harmed, would open the same door for specialist lawyers to sue whenever <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> enacts a statute which impacts on their clientele,'' <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON> said. `` The harm alleged by plaintiffs ... essentially boils down to their perception that their workload will be more complex and will markedly increase,'' <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON> said. `` That sort of ` harm' or ` injury' is no different from the ` harm' that the passage of the Tax Reform Act of 1986 caused for tax laywers, or for that matter than the ` harm' caused for criminal lawyers by the passage of the Bail Reform and Speedy Trial Acts,'' the judge said.
