<HEAD>Japan Asks U.S. to Reconsider Whaling Sanction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is asking the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to reconsider its charges that a Japanese `` scientific research'' whaling expedition in the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> is undermining international agreements, the <ORGANIZATION> Japanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. Ambassador <PERSON> Nobuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Matsunaga </PERSON> sent Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> a letter accusing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of taking `` unilateral action'' and `` unjustifiable measures'' in the whaling dispute, an embassy statement said. It referred to a Feb. 10 <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> declaration that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s killing of minke whales in the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> violated international whaling agreements. The declaration means that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> by April can order a 50 percent cut in the Japanese fishing quota in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic territorial waters and exclude Japanese fish and fish products from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets. The current Japanese fishing quota in the 200-mile offshore <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic zone is zero but the declaration could be applied to future years as well as apply to sales of processed fish. <PERSON> Matsunaga </PERSON>'s letter restated the Japanese government position that the current <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> expedition is for non-commercial research `` provided for in the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Whaling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION>.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> agreed in 1984 that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> would cease commercial whaling in 1987. Critics say that proposed harvest of hundreds of minke whales is excessive for research, that the commission has not specifically authorized the current expedition and that the stated research into whale population, diet and nutrition could be carried out without killing the whales. The Embassy said <PERSON> Matsunaga </PERSON> in his letter, dated Friday, `` strongly urged the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> to reconsider its position in light of the damage these moves would cause to mutually beneficial U.S.-Japan fishery relations.''
