<FIRST>a i PM-Chile-HumanRights Adv29   02-22 0934</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile-Human Rights, Adv 29,0959</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs Feb. 29 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Activists Claim Human Rights Violations More Subtle in Chile</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Open violence against dissidents is now rare in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, but specialists contend that widespread human rights violations continue in more subtle ways and often are cloaked in apparent legality. The 14-year-old military government of President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who also is the army commander, `` has modernized'' its repression methods, claims <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Garreton </PERSON>, chief lawyer for the Vicariate of Solidarity, the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s human rights agency. <PERSON> Garreton </PERSON> and other lawyers and human rights activists contend that the military regime has succeeded in politically neutralizing many dissidents by fear, making violent repression no longer necessary. Speaking in interviews, they said that although torture is still common, the government has developed other, more subtle methods, including the continued enforcement of a nationwide state of emergency that empowers it to severely curtail basic civil rights. The government has also issued a number of specially tailored decrees and laws that give a formal legality to repression and ensure impunity to many human rights violators, the specialists maintain. As an example, they cited the widenening scope of military justice. During the last two years, 95 percent of those tried by military courts were civilians, according to <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Hales </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hales </PERSON> said 90 percent of those tried were eventually freed without charges, but most of them were kept incommunicado for long periods, sometimes up to 40 days. The specialists contended that repression now often works through indimidation and threat, including the action of several shadowy, right-wing extremist groups that kidnap, beat up and occasionally even kill people. Authorities deny any connection with such groups and have promised to investigate. Nearly 200 Chileans claim to have received death threats in recent months from the extremist groups, including some well known dissidents, and many have been briefly kidnapped and physically abused. One group, the September 11 Commando, took responsibility for the killing of five leftists the day after a bloody but unsuccsessful attempt to kill <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> in 1986. Five young Communists have been missing since September, and a group called Chilean Anti-Communist Action claimed responsibility Feb. 15 for their abduction and disappearance. These methods `` have an extremely paralyzing and brutally frightening effect on most people,'' said <PERSON> Garreton </PERSON>. Lawyers and human rights activists, including <PERSON> Hales </PERSON> and <PERSON> Garreton </PERSON>, said they are convinced that those groups are `` centralized'' and connected to official security services. <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Troncoso </PERSON>, research director of the independent <ORGANIZATION> Chilean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said `` threatening is the new tactic for repression.'' The critics point out that, although most cases remain unsolved, every time a member of one of those groups was discovered, he proved to be a member of the military or the security services. An army lieutenant, <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON>, was killed three years ago by a bomb he was planting at a church in the southern city of <LOCATION> Punta </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arenas </LOCATION>. A number of leaflets of the Chilean Anti-Communist Action group were found at the site. <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Volio </PERSON>, a Costa Rican who is the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>' officially designated human rights inspector for <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, has denounced the existence of the extremist groups Unless they are dismantled, he said, `` this society will remain torn apart.'' In the years after <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> and the military seized power in a bloody 1973 coup, hundreds of leftist dissidents were killed, and at least 683 cases of political prisoners who disappeared have been documented by local and foreign human rights groups. The torture of prisoners was considered widespread. Summary executions have long since ceased and arbitrary arrests have decreased sharply. According to figures gathered by the <ORGANIZATION> Chilean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, 33,903 people were arbitrarily arrested in 1986, while the figure went down to 6,255 in 1987. The commission registered 106 cases of torture of dissidents in 1987, compared to 290 a year earlier. The commission's <PERSON> Troncoso </PERSON> stressed in an interview that `` we have never had a single report proved unfounded. We are extremely rigorous. There are many claims we do not publish for lack of evidence.'' Since the 1973 coup, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> regularly has issued reports that are highly critical of the Chilean government. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has also been critical of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> in its annual country-by-country report submitted to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. This year's reports by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, while still critical, noted an improvement in the general situation of human rights here. But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> report mentioned continued torture of prisoners. The government rejected the reports. An official statement said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> report `` reflects only a partial picture of reality, ... has errors and mentions some facts that have not been proved.'' <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Varas </PERSON>, secretary of a government-appointed <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> report shows `` a lack of knowledge of the Chilean situation.'' The government also complains that its critics fail to refer to terrorism by leftist guerrilla groups when discussing the human rights situation. Human rights activists criticize government legislation they contend is tailored to curb dissent. They cite the 1980 Constitution, which outlaws `` totalitarian doctrines,'' such as Marxism, and an amnesty law that they claim favors scores of human rights violators. They also cite the nationwide state of emergency and widened state of siege legislation that severely curtail civil rights and grant authorities wide powers to supress dissent, including the exile of dissidents, banning of public meetings, censorship of the mail and communications and restrictions of freedom of the press and of labor unions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs Feb. 29</NOTE>
