<SECOND>PM-French Education, Adv 01,0899</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs March 1 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>French Concerned about Their Often-Praised Educational System</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s system of education, admired worldwide f, time-proven methods, has become a source of concern in French homes, where it is increasinglyor its rigorous regarded as a misfit in the modern world. To its critics of the late 1980s, it is like a fine old car on a superhighway; it still works and still draws `` ahs'' but needs a tune-up, or an overhaul, to keep up with the traffic. `` The fundamental problems with French education is that it is an extremely selective system and leaves aside too large a proportion of youth who do n't finish their studies,'' said <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertrand </PERSON> of the government-run Center for the Stuy 42 to 43 percent of French students finish high school and only about 22 to 23 percent go on to higher studies at a university or a prestigious `` grande ecole,'' according to <PERSON> Bertrand </PERSON>. About 46 percent of French students receive what is known as `` professional formation'' for a specific trade, be it in a hospital or a bakery. `` We are conscious these levels are no longer adapted to the economic and social needs of today,'' said <PERSON> Bertrand </PERSON>. `` If you compare it to countries like the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, we are far behind.'' The Paris-based <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, which seeks to promote economic and social development in its 19 member countries, agrees with the system's critics. `` The education system is geared toward helping the academically inclined. It is in fact a highly selective system which eliminates the weaker pupils at each different level and tends to brand them as losers,'' it said in a 1984 report on youth employment in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The `` grandes ecoles'' perhaps represent the ultimate example of selection in the education system. Since the 18th century, higher education in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> has been dominated by the elite, specialized schools _ not universities _ which turn out the future leaders of government and industry. One of the `` grandes ecoles'' is the <ORGANIZATION> Ecole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> d'Administration </ORGANIZATION>, whose graduates have a near-monopoly on top jobs in the government bureaucracy and figure prominently in politics. Another is <PERSON> L'Ecole </PERSON> <PERSON> Polytechnique </PERSON>, run by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, which turns out most of the nation's top engineers, many of whom become chief executives in state-owned or private industries. Looking toward a more competitive continent when the European Economic Community's open border policy starts in 1992, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is scrutinizing its education system and finding it heading for, or already in, a state of crisis. Students ill-prepared for the job market, a lack of funds, a top-heavy structure and an aging, diminishing university teaching corps are among other problems. A government-ordered report on university professors, released Feb. 18, spoke of the `` vertiginous degradation'' of their lot, in pay, lack of work incentives and mediocre working conditions. For the student, the lot is determined in a process of selection, with the first at about age 13 based on performance in French and mathematics. Universities present the opposite problem: any student with a baccalaureate from high school can enter. There is almost universal agreement that the 78 state-run universities need to be reformed, but successive governments have faced a student broadside in trying to do so. `` For the past 20 years, the university has been the sick man of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>,'' said the newsweekly Le Point in a cover story on universities. While 80 percent of university graduates find jobs within 10 months of receiving diplomas, 70 percent of the jobs are either administrative or not in the graduate's field. Even critics of the system say a student who passes the baccalaureat, the several-days-long exam at the end of high school, is better equipped academically than an American high school graduate. But, according to current thinking, the student is not necessarily better prepared to meet the requirements of the job market. `` It is generally charged that national education is lagging behind in comparison with the needs of companies,'' <PERSON> Bertrand </PERSON> said. `` In the universities, teaching is mainly theory,'' said a 24-year-old doctoral student, <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillochet </PERSON>. `` When you leave, you have lots in your head but you do n't know how to do anything.'' Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, a presidential candidate in spring elections, was confronted with the issue by an unemployed 24-year-old university graduate during a campaign stop in <LOCATION> Reims </LOCATION>. French education, the premier told the woman, has trained too many people `` in abstract subjects for theoretical jobs.'' `` It's too general. It does not give the technical expertise our businesses demand. Our enterprises need more and more people with technical knowledge.'' Said Bertand: `` The big idea now is ` alternance,' going alternatively to school then a company for training, like in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, to get both theory and experience.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs March 1</NOTE>
