<SECOND>PM-Secret Christians, Adv 02,0920</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs March 2 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Spirit of Japan's Secret Christians Lives On</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OISO, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They worshipped in village homes at night. They hid the symbols of their foreign faith inside <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> altars and images. These were times when their discovery could mean torture or death. They were Japanese who became Christians after St. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Xavier </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in 1549-1551. Today, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s Christians worship freely, but they cherish their secret past. Some 13,000 of the nation's 1 million or so Christians continue the tradition of secret worship, mostly on remote islands in southern <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Most are the elderly who do so out of habit rather than out of fear. And now artifacts of the secret-Christian era, many collected by a woman who once worshipped secretly herself, soon will be displayed in a museum here in <LOCATION> Oiso </LOCATION>. Hundreds of thousands of Japanese embraced Christianity under Jesuit and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> leadership in the 16th century, when Western influence was first felt in their isolated archipelago. The government banned what it regarded as a disruptive foreign religion after Europeans were expelled from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in 1639. In periodic persecutions, suspected Christians were forced to recant, or be tortured, crucified or burned at the stake. But Christians continued to worship privately for more than 200 years, and during that time, Japanese Christianity acquired a unique flavor. The hundreds of statues and scrolls already collected by the museum at <PERSON> Oiso </PERSON> attest to the ambiguity of religion in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, where adherents to various faiths have customarily mixed Christian, <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> and Shinto rituals to mark the major turning points in their lives. As the Christians originally concentrated in <LOCATION> Kyushu </LOCATION> gradually spread throughout <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, they preserved symbols of their faith in hidden ways, said <PERSON> Shigeru </PERSON> <PERSON> Tai </PERSON>, the curator of the museum's collection `` Carpenters built crosses into <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> temples,'' he said. `` They worshipped symbols of fish and family crests that were shaped like crosses, and other Japanese did n't guess those were also Christian symbols. `` In one temple, the walls were studded with cross-shaped windows, but the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- priests had no idea they were made by Christians.'' The secret Christians took advantage of this lack of awareness and of the close similarity of the <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> god of mercy. They painted on their breasts tiny gold crucifixes that apparently passed unnoticed. The back of one artifact, a statue of a Japanese warrior-god brandishing a spear, opens to reveal an ivory and gold crucifix. Other statues have false bottoms, with crosses and icons inside. <PERSON> Tai </PERSON>, 71, was a close friend of <PERSON> Miki </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawada </PERSON>, the woman who collected the treasures and the granddaughter of the founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> industrial empire. After her death in 1980, <PERSON> Tai </PERSON> and others raised the funds for the museum, on the peaceful, forested grounds of the orphanage Mrs. <PERSON> Sawada </PERSON> founded in <LOCATION> Oiso </LOCATION>, 35 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Born into a strict <PERSON> Buddhist </PERSON> family, she learned of Christianity from a nurse when she was 8 years old and worshipped secretly until her 18th birthday, when she was allowed to attend a church service for the first time. She eventually married a Christian and devoted her life and wealth to helping others, establishing the <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON> Home for orphans. The orphanage was named after an impoverished British woman living in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> who contributed her life savings, $ 170, to help establish it. For 40 years, Mrs. <PERSON> Sawada </PERSON> visited communities where secret Christians once lived, collecting their treasures, which are being housed in a tiny chapel before the museum's opening in April. `` These items are priceless,'' said <PERSON> Tai </PERSON>, gingerly uncovering what looks like a metal plate but turns out to be a magic mirror. `` There is only one man in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> who can still make these mirrors.'' Bright light reflected in the rather dull surface of the 16th century mirror casts the shadow of Christ on the cross. To police seeking out Christians at the time, the mirror was just a mirror, but for the secret worshipers, it was a precious symbol of their faith. The prohibition on Christianity, enforced sporadically, was lifted when <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> reopened its door to the West in 1854. Under the militaristic governments during World War II, however, Christianity again became suspect. Some secret Christians willingly worshipped both <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> and Christian deity. Others, forced to demonstrate their piety at temples and shrines, directed their prayers toward crosses etched secretly by other Christians into woodwork or hidden behind <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> altars. When Japanese pray at shrines and temples, they usually clap twice. The Christians would clap once again, the third clap a reminder of the Holy Trinity, <PERSON> Tai </PERSON> said. `` During the war, when <PERSON> Christianity </PERSON> was considered subversive, we used to clap the third clap very quietly,'' he said. Christianity, however, has set down few roots in this syncretic nation, and today attracts less than 1 percent of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s 121 million people. Less than half the Japanese people profess devotion to any faith, but Japanese life is still dominated by <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> and Shinto rites, and most homes have <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> altars for prayers to dead family members. The Christians still living in remote villages in southern <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, who say prayers in an incomprehensible form of pidgin Japanese, are continuing a tradition that is dying elsewhere, <PERSON> Tai </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs March 2</NOTE>
