<FIRST>a i AM-SouthAfrica-MixedRace Adv29   02-22 0991</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Mixed Race, Adv 29,1017</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Feb 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>South African Mixed-Race Leader Makes a Comeback</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>, a mixed-race politician and member of President <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s Cabinet, defied apartheid laws more than a year ago and went swimming at a whites-only beach. Then at <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s demand, he apologized. Doubts immediately arose that the highly regarded <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> would ever regain credibility among his non-white constituents. But he has made a remarkable comeback. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> now is recognized as perhaps the only elected official in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> with both the will and the power to defy the president. As leader of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s mixed-race chamber, he is in a position to force <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to the polls next year, three years earlier than it would like. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> he needs consent from all three chambers of Parliament to delay the election from 1989 to 1992. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> holds 76 of 85 seats in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>, says he wo n't acquiesce unless <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> abandons the government's policy of segregated neighborhoods This demand is unlikely to be met and has resulted in <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>'s forced resignation from the Cabinet. But the confrontation appears to have boosted his popularity among the country's 3 million `` coloreds,'' as mixed-race South Africans are called. `` Suddenly a lot of people who were disinterested or antagonistic are now realizing that you can find yourself in a position of altering the course of history in this country,'' <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>, 60, said at a recent news briefing. `` It does give you and the people you represent a feeling of importance.'' <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>'s political fortunes have seesawed since he helped found the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1969. He was detained for two months in 1976 for his anti-apartheid stance, but came under fire from activists in 1984 when the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> agreed to participate in a new tricameral Parliament setup. Chambers for Asians and coloreds were created to join the dominant white chamber, although the nation's black majority remained excluded. The Asian and mixed-race chambers are allowed to handle their `` own affairs'' _ deciding to how to allocate public funding for their own communities, for example. But the 1984 constitution gives the majority party in the white chamber almost total power to set national policy and to override even combined opposition from the other chambers. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> said he would cooperate with the new system for five years in an effort to dismantle apartheid from within. Activists nonetheless denounced him as a sellout for joining <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s Cabinet as minister without portfolio. `` Our participation within the system must not be construed as an acceptance of the system,'' said <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>. `` We walk the difficult road of being in and yet being out.'' In January 1987, the portly politician made a seemingly bold challenge of the government by wading into the surf at a whites-only beach in <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeth </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, in a televised speech, furiously ordered <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> to apologize or quit the Cabinet. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> apologized. `` It was a demolition job with such humiliation for Rev. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> that he is unlikely to recover from it,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gastrow </PERSON>, chairman of the white opposition <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said at the time. Now, white liberals applaud <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>'s tougher tactics and are considering possible alliances with his <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> still has many detractors, including activists who totally reject the tricameral <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. At the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION>, a leftist, predominantly mixed-race school, <PERSON> Rector </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerwel </PERSON> said <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>'s resurgence had been `` a non-event.'' The pro-government media also has been critical, for different reasons. The Citizen, a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> newspaper, maintained that the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had become `` fractious and militant'' after being set on a `` dangerous collision course'' by <PERSON> Hendricske </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> says he holds no personal animosity toward <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> but is clearly pleased at having found an effective means of challenging him. `` It's not a question of personal power or strength, but rather a recognition of the correctness of the decision to participate -LRB- in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-,'' he said. `` In spite of the constitutional inadequacies, we were able to find a gap, a weakness, and thus find ourselves in a powerful position.'' In addition to his leverage over the election schedule, <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> has blocked a government proposal to begin joint debates among the three parliamentary chambers. Without joint voting and other reforms, the change is meaningless, <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> maintains. Regardless of whether the white election is delayed, <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> wants mixed-race elections to proceed as scheduled next year. Only 30 percent of colored voters went to the polls in 1984, when activists urged a boycott, and <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> says the turnout next year could rise to 50 percent. He said pro-government forces are seeking to weaken him by dividing his party. Allegations have surfaced that <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials tried to bribe <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members into deserting him. There is speculation that <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> may retire soon, and <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> has raised an intriguing scenario regarding the choice of a successor by the electoral college. The college consists of 50 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members, 25 <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members, and 13 members from the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> chamber's majority party. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> says the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> and mixed-race electors could thwart the selection of a hardliner if they could persuade seven or more relatively liberal Nationalists to join them in electing a moderate, such as Foreign Minister <PERSON> Roelof </PERSON> `` Pik'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, no relation to the president. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> was raised in Uitenhage, near <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeth </LOCATION>, the fifth child of a Congregational minister. He grew up in an integrated neighborhood and became a minister himself. In 1971, the mixed-race community was forced to move to a colored township under terms of the Group Areas Act, which mandates segregated neighborhoods. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> has described his father's anguish as he watched their home and church being destroyed Now, he wants the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to abolish the Group Areas Act and says he has done enough compromising.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Feb 29</NOTE>
