<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, March 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Two Centrist Candidates Hold Edge in Venezuelan Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fourteen candidates of various political hues are in the race for <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s presidency, but polls give two centrists the leading edge so far in the campaign for December's balloting. A former anti-government guerrilla hopes to become a serious third option, but the other 11 candidates are given little chance. One of the centrists is <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, who is known as `` The Tiger.'' The other is <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, a former president who has been matching practically every every campaign promise <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> has made. The former guerrilla is <PERSON> Teodoro </PERSON> <PERSON> Petkoff </PERSON>, a Socialist. <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> and <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> represent the two political parties that have dominated Venezuelan politics since dictator <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> was overthrown in 1958 after six years in power. <ORGANIZATION> Accion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratica </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- AD -RRB-, the social democratic party now in power, is fielding <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, a 69-year-old charismatic leader with considerable political experience. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>'s government in 1973-77 is popularly associated with the oil-prices boom in 1974. He is considered to have a slight edge now for the Dec. 4 election, although the 47-year-old <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, the Copei or <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION> candidate, has made inroads by raising the issue of electoral reform. After a shaky start, <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> took the initiative with calls for direct elections of state governors, rather than by presidential appointment, and voting for individual congressional candidates, rather than by party lists. `` I do n't think there is an electoral system in the entire world as primitive as ours,'' <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> told reporters recently. According to a recent <PERSON> Gaither </PERSON> poll done for <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>'s AD, the promise of reform enabled <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> to narrow the distance between him and <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> to 11 percent by late January, from around 30 percent in November. Following <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>'s electoral-reforms proposal, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> came up with one of his own. `` I propose to the nation a Pact for Reform, to deepen and open our democratic system,'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> announced at a public celebration Jan. 23 marking the 30th anniversary of the <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON>'s overthrow The 10-point Pact for Reform contains proposals almost identical to the <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>'s. `` The only thing -LRB- Perez -RRB- has to do now is support my candidacy,'' <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> complained at a recent rally. The two major parties have staked out electoral bases so broad that voters are sometimes hard pressed to see a difference. <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> and <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> preach political reforms of the democratic system, but they agree it should stay democratic. They argue about the degree of state intervention in the economy, but they agree the state should intervene. Copei, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, is considered somewhat more conservative, while AD, which belongs to the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, is more labor-oriented. But they are both centrist. Their members run from conservative to liberal, but most are somewhere in between. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s presidency has flipped back and forth between the AD and Copei five times in the six elections from 1958 to 1983. An AD candidate succeeded an AD president only once. Their success in dominating Venezuelan politics has relegated all the other parties to marginal political roles. The ex-guerrilla <PERSON> Petkoff </PERSON> is carrying the banner of the <LOCATION> Movimiento </LOCATION> <LOCATION> al </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Socialismo </LOCATION>. In the 1960s, when an indigenous guerrilla movement was active, <PERSON> Petkoff </PERSON> preached a socialism bordering on communism. But he gave up his fight, accepting amnesty offered by the government. He moderated his views and is now a member of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. His party dropped its affiliation with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> following the Soviet-led invasion of <LOCATION> Czechoslavakia </LOCATION> in 1968. But even though <PERSON> Petkoff </PERSON> started his campaign by trimming his bushy moustache and longish hair in an effort to dispel any conceptions of radicalism, he is n't expected to win much more than 5 percent of the vote. That was as much as his party got into 1978, its best year. The remaining candidates are even worse off. They are formally in the race but are not making much of a difference. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s first woman presidential candidate, <PERSON> Ismenia </PERSON> <PERSON> Villalba </PERSON>, is running on the slogan, `` <LOCATION> Ismenia </LOCATION>, take her into your heart.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, March 1</NOTE>
