<FIRST>a i AM-LifeAbroad-India Adv02   02-22 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Life Abroad-India, Adv 02,0861</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, March 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LIFE ABROAD: India _ Bullock Carts for the 21st Century</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 This is one of a series of periodic reports by <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> correspondents on the way of life in other countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> is taking the bullock-cart into the 21st century. At least 500 researchers in about a dozen government-aided institutes are at work modernizing the ancient, creaking, plodding carts, and even the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> has donated funds. Carts of various shapes and designs, made of plastic and aluminum, are being tested or have been developed. `` There is nothing funny about our project,'' said <PERSON> Mittar </PERSON> <PERSON> Pal </PERSON> <PERSON> Dhir </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Road </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. `` For us, animal-drawn carts are of great importance.'' <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has an estimated 13 million bullock carts drawn by about 26 million of the neutered bulls, along with 2 million carts pulled by water buffaloes, camels, horses, mules and donkeys. The carts are seen most often in villages, where about 640 million of the <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people live. But they also are seen on major highways and an estimated 3 million plod along city streets, often slowing engine-powered traffic and infuriating motorists. <PERSON> Bullock </PERSON> carts have even been used to pull MiG fighter jets to parades and earth satellites to launching pads. <PERSON> Dhir </PERSON> said it would be 50 years before <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> could eliminate animal-drawn carts, given their crucial role in Indian life. Capital investment in animal-drawn carts is put at $ 7.6 billion. More than 20 million Indians earn their living by driving, renting, and repairing the carts. `` The figure is striking given the fact that Indian railways, the fourth largest in the world, employ only 16.3 million people,'' said <PERSON> Rupinder </PERSON> <PERSON> Gupta </PERSON>, a mechanical engineer for the <ORGANIZATION> Road </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gupta </PERSON> has designed six types of bullock cart for field trials. Each year, animal-drawn carts move 14.4 million ton-miles of freight. Dhir estimates that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s animal-drawn carts provide about 40 million horse-power, equal to about 320,000 medium-duty trucks used in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as city delivery vehicles. Without bullock carts, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> also would have had to import an additional 6 million tons of fuel each year. It now imports 17 million tons of crude oil annually. One of the innovations is the replacement of the carts' wooden-spoke wheels with pneumatic tires Engineer <PERSON> Gupta </PERSON> said carts with pneumatic tires can pull 2.5 tons of weight against the maximum capacity of 1.5 tons for conventional carts. Researchers in the southern state of <LOCATION> Karnataka </LOCATION> also have come up with plastic bullock carts, and in neighboring <LOCATION> Andhra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pradesh </LOCATION> state a tire company has produced carts of lightweight aluminum. Another idea behind non-wooden carts is to reduce demand for lumber. An estimated 165,000 medium-sized trees are felled each year to make conventional carts. `` So you see, there is a solid logic behind metal carts,'' said <PERSON> Gupta </PERSON>. He listed other reasons for updating the carts. `` We want to increase tillage and output, reduce damage to roads and injury to animals so that the poor animals can have a longer lifespan,'' he said. To protect the animals, curved and padded yokes are being introduced. Studies have shown that some draft animals' lives are cut short by cancerous infections on the neck from unpadded and uncurved yokes. Reflectors are being added as another safety feature. Other new fittings are <PERSON> bush </PERSON> bearings, cast-iron springs, shock absorbers, draw bars that adjust for animals of different height, and mud scrappers. A fodder box can be put on carts that go long distances. As for road damage, director <PERSON> Dhir </PERSON> said the biggest culprit is wooden wheels. `` In monetary terms the annual damage is to the tune of 7,000 million rupees -LRB- $ 538 million -RRB- to the roads,'' he said. Farmers seem to like the idea of improving bullock carts. `` It is an excellent idea,'' said <PERSON> Jhandu </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, 64, of <LOCATION> Jharsa </LOCATION>, a village 30 miles south of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. `` But this should have had been done 25 years ago. We have suffered for long, and so did the animals.'' Officials, too, say the new carts are catching on, but this itself is creating problems. `` We do not have enough new types of carts for all,'' said <PERSON> Kalle </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>, project economist of the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jharsa </LOCATION>, whose office received only 16 new carts. `` There are more than 200 claimants. Even some gypsies saw the carts and were attracted. They wanted at least one. I told them no. These are for farmers.'' Another reason for high demand is that the government is subsidizing the price by about 35 percent. It is estimated that the largest of the old wooden carts costs the equivalent of about $ 300. Newer wooden carts, without the government subsidy, cost $ 270 to $ 460. The plastic and aluminum carts are 25 percent more expensive.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, March 1</NOTE>
