<FIRST>s a BC-APN--CrookedMayor Adv06-2Takes   02-22 0856</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Crooked Mayor, Adv 06-2 Takes,0883</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ The former mayor of <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, will be sentenced this week on charges that he extorted hundreds of thousands of dollars from people wanting to do business with the city. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, a Democrat, pleaded guilty to the charges, saying he accepted sole responsibility for what happened.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MIKE HENDRICKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In his day, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> was one of the most visible mayors in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, a politician who seemed destined for bigger things. Now he appears destined for prison. As mayor of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s fifth-largest city, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> had a penchant for beautiful women, chauffeur-driven limos and bodyguards. He was a snappy dresser with a deep tan, his hair always in place. During his 16 years as mayor, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, a Democrat, was often the spokesman for the nation's mayors. He served as president of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION> and six times was elected president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>. There was talk of a big job in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, speculation that he might some day run for governor. Party leaders made him their candidate for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1974, but he lost the primary to former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. Now it turns out the man who looked so urbane and polished was actually an extortionist, using his power to coerce money from people wanting to do business with the city of <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s scheme preyed on architects, lawyers, engineers, and insurance agents. They paid him up to 25 percent of the cost of the project and payments were made in bonds, gold coins and cash. For example, an architect paid <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> $ 125,000 for the opportunity to work on a project at the city's <ORGANIZATION> Hancock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> and another paid $ 25,500 for a hospital parking garage expansion. An insurance agent paid an Alexander bagman $ 26,200 for a fire policy and a lawyer paid a bagman $ 2,878 to handle the legal work on a downtown building project. `` A lot of people turned down the deals and nothing happened,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> was astute enough to know where he could put the pressure. If someone caved in, well, he kept the pressure on. If someone rebuffed him right away, he'd back right up.'' By the time <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> left city hall in 1986, he was a millionaire. Now he has to pay it all back. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> pleaded guilty to charges that he violated federal racketeering laws by using his power as mayor to extort money, that he conspired to obstruct the investigation and that he evaded income taxes on his illegal profits. Sentencing is scheduled for March 10. The federal prosecutor is recommending that <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> be sentenced to 10 years in prison and fined $ 100,000. <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON> said he believes that a 10-year sentence would be longer than any handed to a public corruption figure in the nation. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> could have faced 690 years in prison if convicted on all 40 counts of the original indictment. The former mayor has also agreed to return $ 1.2 million of his illegal profits. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> has said the settlement will leave him in worse financial shape than he was in 1970 when he began his mayoral career. Some of <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s bounty was turned over to prosecutors by attorneys delivering shopping bags filled with valuable bonds and coupons. Some of the money was banked overseas in such places as the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON>. Nine other people who have pleaded guilty to charges stemming from the investigation will be sentenced along with <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s undoing started with <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON>'s appointment as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney for northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1982. <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON>, who grew up in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION> and earned his law degree from <ORGANIZATION> Syracuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said he had heard talk that <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> was crooked. `` This thing really began when I first became <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney,'' <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON> says. `` There were rumors on the street then about <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> being a wheeler and a dealer. If not kickbacks, then there was talk about a lot of conflicts. The rumors were pretty rampant. I decided we should look into it and put them to rest one way or another.'' At first, it was slow going. But the investigation persisted. `` You keep working and working, nibbling away at it, developing whatever information you can,'' <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON> says. `` There was a pattern of no-bid contracts and professional fees. `` We got a couple of breaks. We got lucky.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> joined <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON>'s attorneys in the investigation A witness came forward offering information in exchange for immunity. `` That was the crack in the dam,'' <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON> says. At its peak, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> was the focus of attention of a team of prosecutors, 20 <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents and another 20 <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> agents. What they came up with was enough evidence to persuade a grand jury to indict the mayor. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> always seemed on the verge of becoming a political heavyweight.
</TEXT>
