<FIRST>s a BC-APN--CrookedMayor Adv06-1stAdd   02-22 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Crooked Mayor, Adv 06-1st Add,0829</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>SYRACUSE, N.Y.: political heavyweight.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In 1976, he passed up an opportunity to be an early supporter of <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s presidential campaign to serve as upstate campaign coordinator for the ill-fated campaign of <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. His extortion scheme was designed to increase his influence with national politicians, according to <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON>. `` He wanted to be considered a viable influence on the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and make things happen,'' <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON> said. `` He could get the money where other people could not.'' Many of the kickbacks <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> arranged were made in the form of political contributions to big-time Democrats, <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> were among the recipients. `` Toward the end he sort of lost track of the political contributions,'' <PERSON> Scullins </PERSON> said. `` As he could see his star dwindling the last three or four years, I think he was more concerned about lining his own pockets. He got greedier and greedier as time went on.'' Opponents were critical of <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s frequent trips away from <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, saying he was more interested in traveling than tending to local problems. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> defended his travels, saying he came back with federal money for his city. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> found an opportunity to get some publicity one day when a gunman killed a man, then took a pregnant woman and her baby hostage in a predominantly black neighborhood, holding police off for most of the day. After being held back by police for many hours, news photographers were suddenly allowed to approach the house. The door opened and <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> ran out of the house clutching the baby to his chest. Photographs of the mayor carrying the baby to safety were displayed by newspapers across the country the next day. Black leaders complained that it was the only time <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> had ever visited the neighborhood. On the local level, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> was a skillful and effective politician. Until <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> came along, the Republicans dominated <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Onondaga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> politics. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s campaign not only ended a 16-year Republican rule of the mayor's office, but led the Democrats to control of the common council. Not everyone liked <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>. When shots were fired at his house, police were prompted to build a guardhouse outside the home. City Auditor <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernardi </PERSON> was probably <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s most vocal critic. <PERSON> Bernardi </PERSON>'s complaints were aimed mainly at the way the mayor did business. The auditor said he knew then that the city was paying too much money for projects and was always doing business with the same people. `` I noticed a pattern that if not illegal, and I had no proof of that, it was not in the best interest of the city,'' said <PERSON> Bernardi </PERSON>, who is still the city auditor. Ironically, while <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> was in power, his <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> opponents who controlled surrounding <LOCATION> Onondaga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> were the target of a special prosecutor investigating political corruption. Despite the talk on the street, the special prosecutor did n't pay much attention to the Democrats. The special prosecutor was appointed by then-Gov. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON>, a Democrat, to investigate allegations that Republicans illegally coerced political contributions from public workers. The investigation netted convictions against several key Republicans who claimed they were unfairly singled out for activities common in politics and also practiced by City Hall Democrats. But the crimes of the Republicans pale when compared with what was going on in <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s city hall office. The Republicans were convicted of violations of a state law prohibiting political fund-raising in public buildings and misdemeanors. Juries returned acquittals on the more serious charges. No Republicans went to prison and no Democrats were ever indicted in that special investigation. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> is not talking publicly about his troubles, his lawyer said. After making his guilty plea, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> issued a statement saying the city never paid for any services it did not receive. `` I accept sole responsibility for what happened,'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> said in his statement. `` While pursuing the highest standards of integrity with respect to the conduct of members of my administration, I did not apply those same standards to myself.'' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, a Democrat, is the mayor now, and he runs things differently. Instead of personally selecting who does business with the city, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> has contractors submit competitive bids. Young has a panel study the proposals before a contract is awarded. There are many who still believe <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> was good for <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>. `` I never saw any sign of any wrongdoing,'' says <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Visser </PERSON>, the city clerk who has worked in city hall since 1974. `` He did an awful lot of good for the city and eventually the good will outweigh the bad. If it had not been for the former mayor, the city of <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION> would not be in the great shape it is in today.''
</TEXT>
