<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ The <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> was founded shortly after the turn of the century as a clearinghouse for a free exchange of ideas at a time when inventors were making contraptions that suited their own tastes. Just as it set the standards for the production of automobiles, SAE now is proposing interchangeable parts for spaceships.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BOB DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARRENDALE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An organization of engineers, best known by its initials on motor oil cans, hopes to do for spaceships what it did for automobiles and airplanes. The Society of Automotive Engineers -LRB- SAE -RRB-, founded in 1905, is a global engineering network for the exchange of ideas. Members have included <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, <PERSON> Orville </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Firestone </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Edison </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindbergh </PERSON>. SAE writes standards on such things as what grade of motor oil works best in cold temperatures, how much reflection comes from a taillight lens, the process that makes a brake stop a car. More than 900 standards cover every passenger car. These standards make sure a product performs in a generally expected way. They are guideposts by which government and industry have measured performance for 83 years in self-propelled vehicles. `` We serve the public by getting the technology out so that others can build upon it and use it as a steppingstone without having to reinvent the wheel,'' says <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rumbaugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, executive vice president of SAE. SAE now has its eyes on the stars. It created a space standardization advisory committee, which met for the first time in December, for possible standards on spaceships. SAE hopes to work with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> on guidelines that would reduce confusion, eliminate duplication and cut costs. `` The space program has been so unique, we've been experimenting with technology that is one of a kind,'' says <PERSON> Arshad </PERSON> <PERSON> Hafeez </PERSON>, SAE's aerospace engineer Six of the 25 members on SAE's exploratory committee are from <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>, which wants to have a space station in orbit in the next decade so it can assemble ships in space, among other things. `` It's getting to the point where some standardization will help everybody,'' says <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON>, manager of engineering standards and practices for <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's enough on the horizon that if we do n't do something soon, we could be in big trouble. Everybody will be going in a different direction.'' <PERSON> Rumbaugh </PERSON> adds: `` As they start putting things up there like a space station, you've got to have interchangeability of parts for repair and maintenance. `` You ca n't be coming back down here when a light bulb goes out and build a new one to take back up. Standards allow you to reduce the cost of manufacturing. Making one of a kind costs you a fortune.'' SAE has its world headquarters in a three-story, red brick building about 30 miles north of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Turnpike and Interstate 79. With 52,000 members in 82 countries, it has 25,000 technical papers on file, holds 20 meetings a year, publishes two magazines and has an engineering library. None of the volumes will make a best-seller list, but they titillate engineers. Esoteric titles include: The Internal Combustion Engine In Theory And Practice, volumes one and two; Fuel Alternatives For Spark Ignition And Diesel Engines; Reinforced Thermosetting Plastics For Ground Vehicle Applications; The Toyota Production Method; and Human Tolerance To Impact Conditions As Related To Motor Vehicle Design. Some car manuals are available in Spanish, French and German. Anyone who pours a can of motor oil can notice the letters SAE along with numbers corresponding to the viscosity of the oil. SAE standards cover 11 grades of oil, with lower numbers performing better in lower temperatures. Oil companies voluntarily produce and label their products by SAE standards. Other SAE deeds are less visible. `` A lot of the work is sort of boring,'' <PERSON> Rumbaugh </PERSON> says. `` We do n't have a lot of hoopla. SAE just attempts to get the job done. Oftentimes, a job can get done a heck of a lot better before it gets a lot of media exposure. We prefer to do things before getting the hype.'' SAE was fringhouse for a free exchange of ideas at a time when inventors were making contraptions that suited their own tastes. Each car still has unique style features. But SAE standards cover such things as ounded as a cleahow much light is emitted by headlamps, the shade of red in a taillight, the area of the windshield that should be cleared by a wiper and the size of the lug nuts that hold a rim onto a wheel. SAE also helped develop the closed-in auto body, the self-starter that replaced the hand crank, the hydraulic brake, the synchronized transmissions that eliminated gear noises and led to the automatic transmission, shatterproof glass, power steering and power brakes. `` The American automobile industry has thrived on the principle that the exchange of technical information improves society,'' <PERSON> Rumbaugh </PERSON> says. `` They are less secretive than almost any other industry in the world.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON>, writing in 1980 on The journalists also met with a member of what <PERSON> Bleibtreu </PERSON> said was the Contra human rights commission.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Mayor Invites Reporter Back for Second Look</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 SALT <LOCATION> LAKE </LOCATION> <LOCATION> CITY </LOCATION> _ Mayor <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> <PERSON> DePaulis </PERSON> has invited a reporter to take a second look at the city the newsman described in print as a `` Perry Como kind of place'' where the <ORGANIZATION> Mormon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> dominates daily life. <PERSON> DePaulis </PERSON> says he does n't want to appear defensive but sent a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> inviting <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamb </PERSON> to return for a second look. In his letter Feb. 17, <PERSON> DePaulis </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lamb </PERSON>'s story overlooked the city's rich cultural climate and ethnic diversity, as well as its beautiful mountain scenery. `` I wish he could see the 10th St. Patrick's Day Parade, whose grand marshal this year is consul general of <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, or the Italian-American Columbus Day celebration, ongoing since 1934, or our annual Greek Festival and Hispanic Fiesta,'' <PERSON> DePaulis </PERSON> wrote. The mayor said he might try to find a sponsor for Lamb if the invitation is accepted.
