<HEAD>Lawrenceville Paper Moves to Mornings</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> LAWRENCEVILLE </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION> _ The <ORGANIZATION> Gwinnett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> will convert to morning publication in early May, the newspaper announced in its Feb. 21 editions. It currently publishes in the afternoon five days a week and in the morning on Saturday and Sunday. Executive Editor <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Osteen </PERSON> said, `` moving to morning publication will allow us to produce a more expansive, complete newspaper for our readers. It will also allow our coverage of sports and the stock market report to be more timely.'' The Gwinnett Daily News, purchased in June by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, becomes the second suburban <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> newspaper to switch from afternoon to morning publication. The <ORGANIZATION> Marietta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> announced similar plans earlier this year. In the last 10 years more than 100 afternoon newspapers across the country have switched to morning publication.
