<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Born in a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> hill town, Seka got interested in the porn business through her boyfriend who owned adult bookstores. Today she's a legend in the adult-film industry, as a performer and as an astute businesswoman.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A porn queen who found her way to the other side of the camera is ascending toward the top in a $ 1 billion-a-year business where many women work but precious few call the shots. She's a platinum blonde whose stage name is Seka. At 33, she has appeared in more than three dozen hard-core adult films over the past decade. `` She is still legendary,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Fishbein </PERSON>, publisher of <ORGANIZATION> Adult </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Video </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> magazine. `` When today's generation delves into the adult-film market for the first time, she is still the one they want to see.'' But the big reason for <ORGANIZATION> Seka </ORGANIZATION>'s financial success is that she sued her manager under federal corruption laws and gained control of her name, her films and a business that turns annual profits in six figures. Dressed demurely in a sweater and slacks and tucked into the corner of a dark restaurant, Seka looks every bit the businesswoman she is as chief executive officer of the Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Pearl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Productions </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, which sells everything from lighters with her logo to panties. `` Nobody has ever taken care of me,'' <PERSON> Seka </PERSON> says matter-of-factly, running a bright pink fingernail through her close-cropped, platinum hair. `` And as long as I look after business, nobody ever will.'' Seka -LRB- she will not disclose her given name -RRB- was born in the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> hill town of <LOCATION> Radford </LOCATION>, where the main industry was an arsenal that manufactures dynamite. She married a factory worker before she finished high school, but the marriage did n't last long. `` All I knew was I wanted to be on my own. I wanted to be independent,'' she recalled. `` I did n't want to wake up and have someone next to me saying, ` Fix me coffee and breakfast.''' Her introduction to the porn industry came during the mid-1970s through a boyfriend who owned adult bookstores. The more she became involved in the trade, the more she became convinced, `` I could do it better.'' She worked her way back from the distributors she knew through the bookstore business to the moviemakers themselves, went to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> one bright day in 1977, answered an ad for a nude model, and started working that afternoon. Seka was paid $ 200 for her first movie, a 15-minute, 8mm film. Many of her early films _ she made more than two dozen between 1977 and 1979 _ were only slightly more memorable, although the pay scale improved considerably. She was, however, just another 23-year-old ingenue making adult films, indistinguishable from dozens of other young women in the de rigeur black nylons and garter belts of the times. Then she met a makeup man with big plans. It was 1980 and the home-video market was just beginning to heat up. He made her over, bulked her up with weights and vitamins, changed the way she dressed, and managed her business in the bargain. Her new look debuted in 1981 in Club magazine and the result was booming sales. Yet, after what should have been a very profitable rise to the top of her profession, <PERSON> Seka </PERSON> had to hire an attorney simply to look at her own books. One glimpse and she sued her manager for diverting income. She worked sparingly over the next two years, ultimately finding herself in 1984 with a handsome settlement and control of a potentially lucrative business now that the home-video market was changing the rules of the adult-film game. No longer dependent on recovering most of the costs from theaters, adult film-making became an almost risk-free venture. A handful of pornographers had recognized the home-video market's untapped potential ahead of the major movie studios and already were doing land-office business. A movie that could be made for as little as $ 150,000 if shot on film _ or $ 20,000 if shot directly onto videotape _ becomes a profit-maker after only moderate sales and rentals. That meant an adult film had only to sell about 20,000 videocassettes _ an average wholesale cost of $ 25 per cassette _ to qualify as a megahit. By comparison, a major movie studio needs to sell 50,000 units to approach the same status. And Seka needed only one look to realize that under the new economic reality, age and overexposure were threatening her main asset _ her body. So in 1984 she added a copyright attorney to gain control of her old material, then a contract attorney to make certain she got top dollar for whatever new material she released. She has made just two feature films since then _ only one has been released _ studied diction and elocution and devoted most of her time to mastering business skills: computers, flow charts, marketing and the like. Her return to the adult-film industry as an actress came in a big way with the 1986 film, `` Careful, He May Be Watching.'' The movie, which cost about $ 230,000 to make, stars Seka in a dual role as twins, one evil, one not. She also conceived the story line, developed the script and served as producer. Former porn star actor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Pacheco </PERSON> directed, making the film something of a trailblazing effort from start to finish. `` Careful'' won the Adult Video News awards for best picture and best director, capped off by <PERSON> Seka </PERSON>'s induction into the Hall of Fame. But she says `` Careful'' wo n't begin making money until it's been on the market for about 2 -LCB- years `` I can wait,'' she said. `` I've got some projects, an exclusive magazine deal, things I ca n't talk about in the wings. I've even been offered the opportunity to be in a major motion picture, but there were casting couches behind the screen. `` At least what I do,'' Seka concluded, `` is on the screen.''
</TEXT>
