<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ <PERSON> Janwillem </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Wetering </PERSON> wrote his first book at age 40 after years of hopping around the globe and pursuing an interest in Zen Buddhism. The Dutch-born author, who now lives in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, was interviewed in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> where he was visiting his publisher.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fans of offbeat mysteries set in exotic locales dote on Dutch author <PERSON> Janwillem </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Wetering </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> cop who spent two years in a Zen Buddhist monastery in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. But even though his novels often have a Zen flavor, van de Wetering says the three heroes of what his publisher calls `` the <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> cop series'' are not followers of the Oriental philosophy. `` They've never heard of Buddhism or Zen,'' says <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Wetering </PERSON>, who now makes his home in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, drawn there first by a Zen teacher. `` I mention it sometimes, in a joking manner, because it's popular with the Dutch intelligentsia. The police could n't care less They think it's all long-haired nonsense.'' Yet, their supercool investigations read like they're following the Zen practice of attaining enlightenment by intuitive insight, beyond intellectual reasoning. `` A lot of people do that,'' <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Wetering </PERSON> says. `` If you ca n't figure it out, then do n't try to figure it out but stay with it.'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Wetering </PERSON>, now 56, wrote his first book when he was 40. It was `` The Empty Mirror,'' about his experiences in the Zen monastery. He has written three childrens books, two novels, two books about Zen, a biography of Dutch diplomat-author <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gulik </PERSON> and is best known for 12 mysteries, most set in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>. The first mystery van de Wetering wrote, `` Outsider in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>,'' introduced the wonderfully detached Commissaris, a Dutch municipal police officer, and his underlings in the murder brigade, Adjutant <PERSON> Grijpstra </PERSON> and Sgt. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Gier </PERSON>. `` Originally I wanted to write a realistic book about the police,'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Wetering </PERSON> said during a visit to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to visit his publisher. `` I had been a policeman myself and thought I could do it. It never came off, even at first. None of the characters wanted to do that. `` Grijpstra was going to be the nasty guy. He immediately became sympathetic. He is my Dutchman, my everyman, my superego. He is not into fantasy. I intended him to be pretty dumb but he is n't. `` <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Gier </PERSON> turned out to have tremendous energy that everybody has as a child and then it gets repressed and organized by society. With <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Gier </PERSON> it never got organized. He is not in the police for any good purpose; he's an adventurer. He's tremendously curious; he wants to see what goes on. He does n't necessarily sympathize with goodness and frown on evilness. `` The only one who's got it all together is the Commissaris. He looks like a gray mouse, with his limp, but he really is a combination of them and goes beyond both of them. He is what I think a Zen master ought to be like. The Commissaris is convinced it does n't matter what you do but he will always do the nice thing.'' Two of van de Wetering's mysteries have been made into movies in <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>. Contracts for an American movie have been signed for `` Hard Rain,'' published in 1986 by Pantheon. <PERSON> Ballantine </PERSON> has published all the mysteries and the two books about Zen in paperback. The author, whose name is pronounced yan-villum van de vet-tevin, started visiting a Zen teacher on the coast of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> in the 1960s. In 1975, he and his Colombian wife, <PERSON> Juanita </PERSON>, settled nearby. He became disillusioned with the Zen teacher but stayed in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> because he likes the country. His wife took up gardening. Their daughter is married. `` We live on 60 acres, which is quite normal there,'' he says. `` I see my neighbors when I go look for them. But too many artists hang out in that part of the world. We meet each other in endless encounters that consume too much time. I really have to discipline myself when I go to the post office not to lose all day. `` The weather is so interesting. We all have boats. There's a big colony of seals and we talk about what they do and what bird is coming for the summer or leaving for the winter. `` I have very little discipline. If I do n't want to work, I peer at the window and hope the dog will come in. When I want to work, I'll work through the night and the next day wo n't go to the post office.'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Wetering </PERSON>'s hobby is making junk sculpture, which he displays around his property. `` I was always frantic about finding certain parts. An old man said, ` Just let it come to you.' I do that all the time now. When I turned 50, I was worried about dying. I wanted a vehicle to guide me across _ a horse. The afternoon I thought of it, I went to the beach and found legs and ribs, a sheet of plywood that was a wonderful fit and rope for the tail.'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Wetering </PERSON> learned about the <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> police work during seven years in the reserve police, working mostly nights and weekends. `` I had to do it because I got accused of dodging the draft. I left <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION> when I was 19 and never remembered to come back. It was kind of a punishment. I liked it. After four years I could have quit.'' At 19, van de Wetering went to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to work, then to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> to study philosophy for a year. Dissatisfied with Western philosophy, he spent two years in a Zen monastery in <LOCATION> Kyoto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. After that he worked for a chemical company in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, in real estate in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, returned to <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> to take over his uncle's wholesale textile business. He got bored with that, sold it after seven years and moved to <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. He started to write during the seven years in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>. `` I always wanted to write,'' he says. `` I could n't. I did bits and pieces and articles. I read that <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> started when he was 40. I kept the desire alive. I started writing when I was 40.''
