<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``A Tiger's Tale''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 If an award is given for silliest movie of the year, `` A Tiger's Tale'' is likely to have few serious competitors It's not offensive, not insulting _ just plain silly. And it's too bad because a lot of the ingredients in this romantic comedy had potential for something better. Ingredient No. 1 is <PERSON> Ann-Margret </PERSON>, an actress with so much skill and innate dignity that she almost saves the film. But not quite. She is cast as Rose Butts, the divorced mother of a wild teen-age daughter in a nondescript <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> town. Rose works as a nurse by day but spends her nights nursing lonely drunks. Into her bored, sad life comes her daughter's castoff teen-age boyfriend, <PERSON> Bubber </PERSON>, who becomes smitten with the mother and wo n't take no for an answer Thus begins an unlikely May-December romance between the naive 19-year-old boy and the middle-aged mom. But once the two begin to cuddle, no one seems to know what to do next, least of all scriptwriter <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, who also directs. He diverts our attention to a few subplots. There's <PERSON> Bubber </PERSON>'s dilemma over whether to give up his pet tiger, <PERSON> Valentino </PERSON> -LRB- the most enchanting performer in this flick -RRB- And there's <PERSON> Bubber </PERSON>'s widowed father's dilemma over whether to marry again. The father, a retired veterinarian who keeps snakes around the house, is portrayed by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Durning </PERSON>, another gifted actor whose efforts are wasted here. Finally, a crisis is created to bring <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bubber </PERSON> back in focus. It turns out that her daughter, <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON>, enraged by Mom's unconventional affair, has had her revenge When she left to live with her father, she poked a hole in <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>'s birth control device. Can you guess the result? The rest of the plot is so preposterous you have to laugh. It should be mentioned that a major flaw from the outset is the lack of even the smallest spark of chemistry between Ann-Margret and her teen-aged lover, <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>, a gangly, wholesome kid with a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> accent who would seem more likely to fall in love with a horse. `` A Tiger's Tale'' is rated R for sexual subject matter.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> rating definitions: G _ General audiences. All ages admitted. PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be suitable for children. PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children. R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian. X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age restrictions.
