<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Istomin Adv4-6   02-22 0908</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Istomin, Adv 4-6,0947</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv4-6</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, March 4-6 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Hitting the Road With a Steinway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Concert pianist <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Istomin </PERSON> has loaded his Steinway on a van and is driving from town to town for his 1988 tour _ an unusual way for classical musicians to hit the road. `` It has n't been done this way for 50 years at least,'' <PERSON> Istomin </PERSON> says. `` Paderewski -LRB- the Polish pianist and composer who died in 1941 -RRB- had a private railroad car. `` There are a lot of places on my tour where so-called ` big name' artists do n't go. The seating capacity of halls is small and people ca n't afford to pay very high fees.'' <PERSON> Istomin </PERSON> is accepting what he terms `` reasonable'' fees. `` I'm playing in a lot of communities which would otherwise not hear me, on a magnificently prepared, superb piano, playing a good program. It's giving me a lot of gratification.'' From January through May, his solo piano recitals are east of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The western tour will start in September in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Istomin </PERSON>, whose wife, <PERSON> Marta </PERSON>, is artistic director of the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Performing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, is always on the move. Last fall, he played a recital in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, ate a sandwich in his hotelroom at midnight, arose at 5 a.m. to fly to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> where he boarded the Concorde to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He was met at <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, handed a tuxedo, taken to rehearsals for the Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award show and played that night on the televised show to honor <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>. `` You can not perform to your maximum ability, doing it this way, and I did n't,'' he said. `` It's the wrong way to do things.'' His intention now is to perform by making short hops from town to town for a few years or more. `` This tour is the right way to do things,'' he said. `` When you play, it does n't have to be only for the fancy swells and sophisticates. The same kind of people, who read the same kind of books and listen to the same kind of music, live in smaller towns.'' The tour began at a college in <LOCATION> Winter </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, with the second concert at a senior citizens center outside <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Istomin </PERSON> has two programs. Program A includes <PERSON> Bach </PERSON>, <PERSON> Schubert </PERSON>, <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>, <PERSON> Debussy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chopin </PERSON>. He has recorded Program B for <ORGANIZATION> ADA </ORGANIZATION>, a French company that releases compact discs. He calls it `` a bit more esoteric. <PERSON> Schumann </PERSON>'s ` First Sonata' is n't often played. It was written to murder the hands of pianists. It's terribly difficult and beautifully inspired, not the kind of piece you normally take on a barnstorming tour.'' He also will play <PERSON> Debussy </PERSON> and some infrequently heard <PERSON> Rachmaninoff </PERSON> on Program B. `` That's what my pianos really serve for,'' <PERSON> Istomin </PERSON> said. `` These pieces require a sophisticated brand of piano playing I can offer with these instruments.'' <PERSON> Istomin </PERSON> has been thinking about a tour such as the one he's doing for years `` I started playing at 17. I played 200 concerts in my first two seasons. I was soloist with the <ORGANIZATION> Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION>, paid $ 250 a week by <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>.'' His first of more than 40 recordings was <PERSON> Bach </PERSON>'s `` D Minor Piano Concerto'' with the Busch players in 1945. `` I played concerts with umbrellas stuck under the sounding board and keys that would n't go down,'' he said. `` I would complain. People would say, ` He's a nasty young man.' The good part of it was that some very high-level music-making was done. I was part of it. I know we had a lot of success and people enjoyed the concerts.'' He'll probably give 100 concerts this year, too. `` I had the stamina half a century ago. I hope I have it now,'' the artist said. `` I'm 62. I feel like I'm 26 and hysterical. I think I never grew up. `` The concerts are strenuous but the traveling is easier these days.'' Cities are not more than 300 miles apart; <PERSON> Istomin </PERSON> and the piano technician drive by car, and luggage oes in the van with the piano. `` I like playing in unpretentious circumstances,'' he said. `` Pretention is not the same as excellence. I think the public, wherever the town, is people who react to and feel what is happening. To me, that's the whole meaning of this trip. `` I'm not warming up for a program in some big hall. I've already played these pieces in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> I want to play in Winter Park, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, the way I play in <LOCATION> Carnegie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hall </LOCATION>. `` Sometimes people ask me to sign a program they've saved 35 years. Those people touch me. I want to do something really nice for those people, for whom music really matters.'' <PERSON> Istomin </PERSON> played at a General Motors cancer research award dinner in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in 1981. `` They sent me a check for $ 7,000, my regular fee. I sent it back, donating it to <ORGANIZATION> Sloan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kettering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>. They were touched by that and said to let them know if there was ever anything they could do for me. When I started thinking about this tour, I thought maybe they would help me.'' <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> designed a van, with a hydraulic lift and temperature control, to carry <PERSON> Istomin </PERSON>'s piano and is lending it to him free. The tour itself does n't have corporate sponsorship.
</TEXT>
