<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--HomeImprovements:ChainSaws     02-22 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Home Improvements: Chain Saws,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>HOME IMPROVEMENTS: Chain Saws</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY709</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Chain saws have become familiar workhorses around the home as homeowners use them to cut firewood and roots, clear storm damage and trim trees and large shrubbery. But many chain saw owners do not know how to take care of them properly and can end up with costly repair bills. A chain saw owner needs to perform an annual maintenance check to ensure trouble-free operation. Solo Inc. experts have developed a 10-step maintenance checklist that can be performed with a few standard tools and a little spare time. You are advised to check the owner's manual for specific maintenance instructions and to perform the procedures during the `` off'' season. For safety reasons, always wear gloves and safety glasses when following these steps in maintaining your chain saw: 1. Drain any remaining fuel from the saw's tank or run the engine until it is empty. 2. Using a garden hose, clean the entire unit while being careful not to get water into the gas tank. 3. Remove and clean saw chain, bar and guide bar. Do n't forget to wear gloves. 4. Remove spark plug and replace it with a new one every year. Be sure to set the correct spark plug gap. 5. Close the choke and remove the air filter assembly. Clean the filter with a stiff paint brush and soap and water or replace it if necessary. 6. Remove the fuel cap, locate the fuel pick-line inside the tank and `` fish'' it out. You may want to use an 8-inch piece of coat hanger that has a `` U'' bend at one end. Replace line or filter if dirty and put cap back on the tank. 7. Use an allen wrench or screwdriver to remove the starter assembly. Clean filter openings with a rag or brush, remove debris and replace any worn parts. 8. Visually inspect all vibration isolators to be sure they are not worn out, torn, cracked, broken or loose. Check manual for exact locations of isolators. 9. Check spark plugs arrestor screen for buildup and clean or replace if rips or performations are present. Clean with water or a wooden `` pop'' stick, making sure not to tear holes in the filter. 10. With gloves on, grasp muffler to check that it is not loose and does not rattle. Replace if necessary. When finished, double check to make sure all parts have been properly replaced, all screws and bolts have been tightened and there are no pieces left over.
</TEXT>
