<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>HOME IMPROVEMENTS: Briefs</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Housing construction for 1987 dropped to 1.62 million units, the slowest building pace for the housing industry since the recession year of 1982, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported. The total compared to construction of 1.81 million units in 1986, which had been an exceptionally strong year for the industry. In 1982, 1.06 million units were built. Analysts blamed much of the weakness on widespread overbuilding in the apartment sector and the adverse effects of the new tax law on real estate investments. Building permits for the year totaled 1.54 million units, 13.1 percent below 1986 and the weakest showing since 1982.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Sales of new homes in 1987 fell 10.1 percent below the 1986 level, the government has reported. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said that sales totaled 674,000 units, compared with sales of 750,000 units in 1986.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 How-to videotapes, for rent or sale, are available in many home centers, hardware stores and lumber yards and some libraries and video stores. Brands include Hometime, <PERSON> Wally </PERSON>'s Workshop, <ORGANIZATION> Ortho </ORGANIZATION> and The DIY Show. Hometime, of <LOCATION> Eden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prairie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, has 27 titles for under $ 10 each. -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trucks </ORGANIZATION> has underwritten the productions in return for a commercial on each tape. -RRB- New titles from Hometime include `` Plumbing'' -LRB- how to plan for and install a new bathroom -RRB-, `` Furniture Refinishing'' -LRB- including stripping -RRB-, and `` Lighting'' -LRB- indoor and outdoor projects -RRB-.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Sales of existing homes held steady in 1987 at close to 4 million units despite volatile mortgage rates and the October stock market collapse, a national real estate trade group reported. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said that sales of existing single-family homes and condominiums totaled 3.885 million units last year, down a slight 0.3 percent from the 1986 level of 3.897 million units. Sales in both years were the fastest pace of this decade. Meanwhile, the average price of an existing home rose to a nationwide median of $ 84,900, an increase of 5.1 percent in 1987, slightly ahead of the rise in consumer prices, the association said.
</TEXT>
