<HEAD>Midam, First Commodity Reach $3.51 Million Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> MidAmerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> have agreed to a $ 3.51 million settlement ending all fraud litigation against <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION>, the exchange announced Monday. Under the agreement, $ 3.01 million will be paid directly to defrauded customers, whose losses totaled more than $ 51 million in 1984, the exchange said in a news release. MidAm will retain <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 500,000 guarantee deposit and the now-defunct firm waived all claim to those funds, the news release stated. <LOCATION> MidAmerica </LOCATION> in 1986 found that <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> had violated exchange rules through its use of promotional materials, fraudulent and misleading sales practices and its withdrawal of guarantee funds on deposit with the exchange. The exchange expelled the company and fined it $ 3.51 million. First Commodity later went out of business. `` Plaintiffs in the class action applaud the MidAm's efforts and contributions in helping settle the largest reported class action commodity fraud settlement to date,'' said <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, one of the plaintiffs' <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> attorneys. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, general counsel for <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION>, could not be reached to comment immediately on the settlement. An answering service collected requests for comment from the defunct firm. `` The MidAm Board of Directors felt this settlement met all the objectives of the exchange, the futures industry, and the needs of defrauded investors,'' said <LOCATION> MidAmerica </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON>. The agreement stipulates that <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> will pay $ 3.01 million to a settlement fund to be administered by the federal district court in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, where investor cases were consolidated. The fund will be used to compensate those investors for some of their losses. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> `` has preliminarily approved a settlement class of potentially defrauded <ORGANIZATION> FCCB </ORGANIZATION> customers eligible for compensation. This settlement raises the amount in the fund to a currently estimated $ 5.3 million,'' the exchange stated. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Murschel </PERSON>, an exchange spokesman, said he did not know how many investors were involved, but the release said `` virtually every FCCB customer lost money, most of them losing 50-90 percent of their investments. `` Customer out-of-pocket losses in 1984 totaled in excess of $ 51 million, nearly $ 30 million of which went to <ORGANIZATION> FCCB </ORGANIZATION> in the form of commissions,'' the exchange said.
