<HEAD>Pan Am, Teamsters in Standoff; Some Agents Report Bookings Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and the union representing 4,500 ground employees in 14 cities remained in a stalemate Monday following the breakup of their talks, and Teamster leaders vowed `` guerrilla war'' against the financially troubled airline. Travel agents reported that some customers have shunned <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flights as a result of the conflict, which was sparked after the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>' strike deadline passed at 12:01 a.m. Sunday. Talks in which management was seeking $ 35 million in concessions from the union broke down Sunday afternoon. No negotiating sessions were held Monday. The union, which represents reservation clerks and other ground staff, put off a strike. But Teamster leaders threatened to use disruptive tactics against <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>, which operates <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, a Northeast corridor air shuttle and other services. Labor unrest also escalated at another major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline. Flight attendants at Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> have voted overwhelmingly to strike this weekend if a contract dispute over wages and benefits is not resolved, a union official said. Disclosure of the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> strike vote came as the two sides readied to resume negotiations for the first time since last month. Sources close to <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they were pessimistic about the prospects for a negotiated resolution of the conflict with the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>. `` We can strike -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- any time we want,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Genoese </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>' airline division. `` We're going to pick our strategic time.'' In the meantime, <ORGANIZATION> Genoese </ORGANIZATION> said, `` there's guerrilla war at all the airports. ... The passengers are really going to suffer in this situation.'' He said the tactics would include deliberately misdirecting baggage and cargo and canceling passengers' reservations <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON> said there was no evidence so far of such disruptions. `` The operation is running smoothly,'' <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON> said. `` There is no evidence of any job action of any sort at any station.'' She said `` nothing very dramatic'' had happened at <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s major hub. The company has said it would maintain operations with replacement workers in the event of a strike. The <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> voted Friday not to support a <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>' strike, and pilots, flight attendants and flight engineers are not expected to honor picket lines. `` There have n't been any problems whatsoever,'' said <PERSON> Archie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenzi </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> pilots union's Master Executive Council, noting that he piloted a flight Sunday from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> without incident. Not all travelers appear to be reassured, however. `` It's a very bad situation for everybody,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Perlman </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> DMS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> in midtown <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. `` Some people are shying away -LRB- from <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flights -RRB-.'' <PERSON> Perlman </PERSON> said his agency has been using double bookings as an insurance technique for customers booked on <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flights. For passengers taking <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> airport to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> on Monday night, for example, he also booked them on flights offered by other airlines to the same destinations. `` I think we have to go on the assumption that if there is a strike, all -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- flights will be shut down,'' <PERSON> Perlman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cammisa </PERSON>, a travel industry consultant, estimates that a threatened strike against an airline generally reduces bookings for the carrier by about 10 percent to 20 percent. `` Any kind of strike threat erodes bookings,'' <PERSON> Cammisa </PERSON> said, noting that the same thing has happened with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of giant <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> with a history of labor troubles. `` The public is very concerned about the turmoil -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZAT