<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock-index futures overcame selling resistance Monday to settle at their highest values since the Oct. 19 stock market collapse. On other markets, cotton futures collapsed; grains and soybeans were mostly lower; livestock and meat were mixed; precious metals were mixed; and energy futures were lower. The contract for March delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 stock index gained 3.90 points to settle at 266.85 on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, topping the previous post-collapse high of 264 points set Jan. 5. The March contract had rallied above the psychologicially important 264-point barrier earlier in the session only to fall back. But the second surge inspired broad-based follow-through buying that continued until the close, indicating the market had potential to move even higher, said <PERSON> Abbe </PERSON> <PERSON> Cocuzza </PERSON>, stock-index strategist for <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Cocuzza </PERSON> speculated the next point of resistance was 274 points, the level at which the March S & amp; P 500 contract opened on Oct. 19 after hitting a low of 280.40 in the previous session. Cotton futures prices collapsed on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in a sell-off linked to the impending expiration of the March contract. Tuesday marks the first notice day for the March cotton contract. Traders holding `` long,'' or buy, positions rushed to liquidate those positions to avoid the possibility of being locked into agreements to take physical delivery of cotton on the contract's March 9 expiration date, analysts said. The sharp decline in the March contract's price touched off computerized sell programs that drove prices on the three near-term contracts down the daily limit and sent prices on other contracts to new life-of-contract lows, said <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, cotton specialist for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The contract for March delivery of cotton settled at 60.40 cents a pound, down the 2-cent limit. Grain and soybean futures finished mostly lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. A mixed opening was followed by firmer prices across the board, but the gains did not hold as commission houses became heavy sellers of soybeans and soybean oil near the close, said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader for <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The beans and oil were the two markets that really collapsed, and that collapse pulled everything else down,'' he said. Wheat settled -RCB- cent lower to 1 \ cents higher with March at $ 3.22 \ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2 \ cents lower with March at $ 1.99 \ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1 cent lower with March at $ 1.90 -RCB- a bushel; soybeans were 6 -LCB- cents lower to 3 cents higher with March at $ Cattle futures declined while pork futures rose on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Profit-taking and hedge selling pressured the cattle contracts, and the pork complex rallied on better-than-expected cash prices, analysts said. Live cattle were .15 cent to .75 cent lower with April at 72.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to 1.03 cents lower with March at 82.52 cents a pound; hogs were .12 cent to .33 cent lower with April at 44.05 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.10 cents lower to .35 cent higher with February at 54.02 cents a pound. Gold retreated slightly while silver gained a bit in light trading on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Gold settled 20 cents to 80 cents lower with April at $ 447.60 a troy ounce; silver was 1 cent higher across the board with March at $ 6.41 a troy ounce. Oil prices edged lower after fluctuating in a narrow range. Some analysts cited reports of overproduction and other problems within the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries that could point to bigger oil supplies. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 8 cents to 25 cent lower with March at $ 16.62 a barrel; heating oil was .01 cent to .56 cent lower with March at 45.79 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .05 cent to .25 cent lower with March at 46.32 cents a gallon.
