<HEAD>Arco Alaska Plans To Spend More Than $7 Billion In Alaska Over 10
Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Richfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> subsidiary said Monday it is prepared to invest more than $ 7 billion in the oil-rich state over the next 10 years if petroleum prices and tax policies are stable. About $ 3 billion would go toward development of known reserves, <ORGANIZATION> Arco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. President <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Anchorage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> Spending of the rest would depend on the discovery of new oil fields, including any reserves under the <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION> if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> allows exploration there. `` To accomplish all of this will require reasonable oil prices and a stable tax policy,'' <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> said. The plan assumes prices in the $ 20-per-barrel range for a few years, followed by increases in the mid-1990s, said <ORGANIZATION> Arco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>. She said <ORGANIZATION> Arco </ORGANIZATION> has not asked for any changes in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s tax structure and does not plan to in the near future. <ORGANIZATION> Arco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> operates half the giant <ORGANIZATION> Prudhoe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> oil field, which along with other North Slope oil fields supplies 20 percent of the nation's domestic oil.
