<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar fell to the lowest trading level in two weeks in early <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> trading Tuesday due to further selling by foreign banks. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency opened at 129.27 yen, down 0.68 yen from Monday's close of 129.95, and was quoted at between 128.85 and 129.35 two hours after the start of trading. On the stock market, share prices rebounded from morning lows and were little changed by mid-day. The Nikkei index of 225 selected issues ended the morning session at 24,860.28, up 13.57 points, or 0.05 percent, from Monday's close. The index rose about 100 points in the last 30 minutes of the morning session from a trading level of around 24,759. Volume by the end of the morning session was estimated at 330 million shares, down from 450 million shares during Monday's morning session Finance Minister <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> told a news conference Tuesday that the higher prices of stocks on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> reflected <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s sound economic fundamentals and optimism by investors about the future.
