<HEAD>Announces Introduction of New Soft Drink</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Seven-Up </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> will introduce an amber colored soft drink labeled 7-Up Gold designed to reach young adults, company officials said Monday. The company is characterizing the new product as `` the wild side of 7-Up,'' a natural spice flavored soft drink sweetened with aspartame. `` 7-Up Gold is the missing link in the 7-Up family,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Albers </PERSON>, chief executive officer of the company, a subsidiary of the Dallas-based investment group <ORGANIZATION> Hicks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Haas </PERSON>. Company officials said they are trying to reach a mostly male 18 - to 34-year-old market with the new drink The company also will introduce a Diet 7-Up Gold. <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, senior vice president of marketing, said that while the image of 7-Up is clean-cut and conservative, 7-Up Gold is aimed at mainstream soft drink consumers who generally drink colas. But like all 7-Up products, it will be `` light, refreshing, thirst quenching, crisp, natural and translucent,'' <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> said. Shipments of the new drink will begin in April, in time for the spring and summer seasons, with national distribution expected by the end of May, officials said. The company will spend more than $ 10 million in advertising for the drink this spring and summer, <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> said. The new drink follows the introduction of Cherry 7-Up and Diet Cherry 7-Up last year. Those drinks have captured 1.7 percent of the lucrative soft drink market. <PERSON> Albers </PERSON> said 7-Up Gold now gives the company `` the most complete, competitive line-up'' in the soft drink industry.
